WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.540 --> 00:00:08.970
Good evening, friends.

00:00:08.970 --> 00:00:10.190
I'm Homi Bhabha.

00:00:10.190 --> 00:00:15.420
I direct the Mahindra
Humanity Center.

00:00:15.420 --> 00:00:20.150
And I'm delighted to
have you here today

00:00:20.150 --> 00:00:32.640
in the company of four
extremely interesting analysts

00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:39.600
who will take up this issue
of democracy in distress.

00:00:39.600 --> 00:00:44.490
Sreenivasan Jain, who is our
featured speaker and visitor

00:00:44.490 --> 00:00:48.780
at the Humanities Center
is Managing Editor

00:00:48.780 --> 00:00:54.150
of the New Delhi Television,
NDTV, India's most respected 24

00:00:54.150 --> 00:00:57.190
hour news and current
affairs broadcaster.

00:00:57.190 --> 00:01:00.900
He anchors an award winning
weekly ground reportage

00:01:00.900 --> 00:01:05.610
and investigative show
called "Truth Versus Hype"

00:01:05.610 --> 00:01:09.480
which focuses on political
corruption, conflict zones,

00:01:09.480 --> 00:01:13.350
and untold stories
of social tensions

00:01:13.350 --> 00:01:15.930
and economic inequalities.

00:01:15.930 --> 00:01:20.730
He also anchors a daily show
called "Reality Check" which

00:01:20.730 --> 00:01:26.580
aims at debunking official
myths and government propaganda.

00:01:26.580 --> 00:01:32.190
He has been with NDTV since 1995
during which he has done stints

00:01:32.190 --> 00:01:36.790
as managing Editor of Profit
NDTV's business channel

00:01:36.790 --> 00:01:42.300
and as head of NDTV Mumbai
bureau for eight years.

00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:44.560
Welcome, Vasu.

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:50.520
Sugata Bose is Gardner Professor
of Oceanic History and Affairs

00:01:50.520 --> 00:01:53.970
at Harvard and a
member of the Indian

00:01:53.970 --> 00:01:58.350
Parliament for the
[INAUDIBLE] constituency.

00:01:58.350 --> 00:02:00.840
His books include
Nation as Mother

00:02:00.840 --> 00:02:03.870
and other Visions of
Nationhood and His

00:02:03.870 --> 00:02:07.050
And Majesty's opponent,
Subas Chandra Bose,

00:02:07.050 --> 00:02:10.530
and India's struggle
against empire.

00:02:10.530 --> 00:02:11.470
Welcome, Sugata.

00:02:14.510 --> 00:02:17.240
Rohit De is a lawyer
and Assistant Professor

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:19.280
of History at Yale.

00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:22.880
His book, A People's
Constitution The Everyday Life

00:02:22.880 --> 00:02:26.030
of Law in the Indian
Republic, explores

00:02:26.030 --> 00:02:29.660
how the Indian Constitution
came to permeate everyday life

00:02:29.660 --> 00:02:33.320
and imagination in India
during its transition

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:38.310
from a colonial state to
a democratic republic.

00:02:38.310 --> 00:02:41.810
Ayesha Jalal is Mary
Richardson Professor of History

00:02:41.810 --> 00:02:44.960
and Director of the South
Asian and Indian Ocean Studies

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:46.280
at Tufts.

00:02:46.280 --> 00:02:49.160
Her books include The
Struggle for Pakistan:

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:52.550
A Muslim Homeland
and Global Politics

00:02:52.550 --> 00:02:55.550
and The Pity of
Partition Manto's Life,

00:02:55.550 --> 00:03:02.200
Times and Works Across
the India-Pakistan Divide.

00:03:02.200 --> 00:03:08.180
Now, skeptical as I am
of global descriptions

00:03:08.180 --> 00:03:13.520
and global prescriptions,
I feel somehow

00:03:13.520 --> 00:03:18.590
that the term
democracy in distress

00:03:18.590 --> 00:03:24.710
has a resonance across
several countries

00:03:24.710 --> 00:03:28.150
and indeed continents.

00:03:28.150 --> 00:03:32.060
We usually spoke of
democracy in distress

00:03:32.060 --> 00:03:37.660
with an Utopian eye
and a Utopian vision.

00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:43.090
The distresses of democracy
were its deficits.

00:03:43.090 --> 00:03:47.680
And we often felt that through
political organization,

00:03:47.680 --> 00:03:53.620
legal reformation, we would
be able to actually overcome

00:03:53.620 --> 00:03:56.980
these democratic deficits.

00:03:56.980 --> 00:04:00.070
Even though that
might be a very a way.

00:04:00.070 --> 00:04:05.470
But it was part of a certain
progressive vision that we had,

00:04:05.470 --> 00:04:09.970
what Derrida once called
the democracy to come.

00:04:09.970 --> 00:04:13.650
It was an aspiration.

00:04:13.650 --> 00:04:19.930
Today, it seems to me, that
various democratic practices

00:04:19.930 --> 00:04:26.440
and institutions have somehow
turned against themselves.

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:32.110
Are confronted with a
strange alienating vision

00:04:32.110 --> 00:04:35.640
of the democratic
process as if they

00:04:35.640 --> 00:04:39.250
are struck with a kind
of autoimmune disease.

00:04:39.250 --> 00:04:44.950
As if the beast and the body
is being consumed from within.

00:04:44.950 --> 00:04:48.000
The democratic body has
turned against itself.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:57.320
As we know that as we bemoan
many anti-democratic movements,

00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:01.480
these are movements that
have been instituted

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:05.290
through democratic
voting patterns

00:05:05.290 --> 00:05:07.090
and through democratic
institutions.

00:05:07.090 --> 00:05:10.630
Whether or not they have
been subject to corruption

00:05:10.630 --> 00:05:14.180
or subject to manipulation
or nepotism is an issue.

00:05:14.180 --> 00:05:19.240
But this notion of
an autoimmunity kind

00:05:19.240 --> 00:05:23.710
of a devouring from
within, strikes me

00:05:23.710 --> 00:05:27.060
as this particular
kind of distress

00:05:27.060 --> 00:05:28.327
that we're witnessing now.

00:05:28.327 --> 00:05:30.160
And of course, there
have been other moments

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:32.320
such as the interwar
period in Europe

00:05:32.320 --> 00:05:35.570
where something very
similar was happening.

00:05:35.570 --> 00:05:40.540
But of course today,
this autoimmune disease

00:05:40.540 --> 00:05:45.970
afflicts the US, India,
Turkey, Pakistan, Venezuela,

00:05:45.970 --> 00:05:47.840
Philippines.

00:05:47.840 --> 00:05:50.450
Of course in each case,
in its different ways.

00:05:50.450 --> 00:05:52.060
But I want to
emphasize that this

00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:55.600
is a kind of global condition.

00:05:55.600 --> 00:05:59.560
But of course to make the
global a critical hermeneutic,

00:05:59.560 --> 00:06:02.560
we can't simply
rest on comparisons.

00:06:02.560 --> 00:06:05.410
We have to talk about
systemic differences

00:06:05.410 --> 00:06:08.380
and structural issues.

00:06:08.380 --> 00:06:11.380
There is, we believe, a
crisis in certain voting

00:06:11.380 --> 00:06:13.960
practices and patterns.

00:06:13.960 --> 00:06:18.250
A crisis in political volition.

00:06:18.250 --> 00:06:22.210
A crisis in
constitutional issues.

00:06:22.210 --> 00:06:25.360
A crisis in
demographic situations.

00:06:25.360 --> 00:06:28.480
And a crisis of a kind
and civil society.

00:06:31.280 --> 00:06:34.660
What I'm calling the
autoimmune condition,

00:06:34.660 --> 00:06:38.560
the destruction from
within, reminds me

00:06:38.560 --> 00:06:42.880
as I was jotting down
these notes of a statement

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:48.670
by Theodore Adorno
in Minima Moralia.

00:06:48.670 --> 00:06:52.660
Well Adorno says
that he was less

00:06:52.660 --> 00:06:58.510
threatened by the frank
face, the frank visible face

00:06:58.510 --> 00:07:03.100
of fascism than
he was threatened

00:07:03.100 --> 00:07:11.180
by the fascistic elements
within social democracy.

00:07:11.180 --> 00:07:18.540
And it is with this rise of this
peculiar hybrid monster which

00:07:18.540 --> 00:07:22.260
has reared its head before
of a democratic process

00:07:22.260 --> 00:07:26.266
and a despotic
tyrannical politics

00:07:26.266 --> 00:07:30.860
that I believe we should
concern ourselves today,

00:07:30.860 --> 00:07:35.110
this doubly articulated world.

00:07:35.110 --> 00:07:39.210
One of the issues that
brings me to Basu's

00:07:39.210 --> 00:07:44.250
important contribution
today of forms

00:07:44.250 --> 00:07:48.720
of democratic
distraction, the forms

00:07:48.720 --> 00:07:50.970
of the perversions
and disfiguring

00:07:50.970 --> 00:07:56.430
of what we call free speech and
free expression in the media

00:07:56.430 --> 00:07:57.000
itself.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:02.940
It seems to me as if there is a
continual speeding up, an over

00:08:02.940 --> 00:08:08.910
talking, which produces a kind
of a dialectic of deletion.

00:08:08.910 --> 00:08:14.880
That the more you hear the
continual facts, the news

00:08:14.880 --> 00:08:20.950
cycle as such, that it's very
difficult actually to grasp

00:08:20.950 --> 00:08:23.770
a thread, to grasp
an argument, to grasp

00:08:23.770 --> 00:08:27.695
a particular direction.

00:08:27.695 --> 00:08:33.000
You know, Gramsci once said,
again very relevantly I think,

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:38.220
the whole question of
hegemonic discourse

00:08:38.220 --> 00:08:42.510
should be understood
in media terms

00:08:42.510 --> 00:08:46.520
like turning up the
volume of a radio.

00:08:46.520 --> 00:08:51.210
So the hegemony
creates for itself this

00:08:51.210 --> 00:08:54.100
dominating soundscape.

00:08:54.100 --> 00:08:58.080
And in many democratic
countries initially,

00:08:58.080 --> 00:09:04.140
although perhaps not at the end
of the process, voices emerge.

00:09:04.140 --> 00:09:07.590
Voices become fainter,
and fainter, and fainter.

00:09:07.590 --> 00:09:10.890
The effort for representation
becomes more dangerous

00:09:10.890 --> 00:09:12.670
and more difficult.

00:09:12.670 --> 00:09:17.240
And suddenly, when
we least expect it,

00:09:17.240 --> 00:09:23.820
the sounding of the
state is so loud

00:09:23.820 --> 00:09:25.650
that all other
voices are stilled.

00:09:28.185 --> 00:09:34.370
Basu's contribution
has been valiant.

00:09:34.370 --> 00:09:39.980
In a context in India
where one gets addicted,

00:09:39.980 --> 00:09:47.610
it is indeed I am addicted, to
late night political programs.

00:09:47.610 --> 00:09:50.430
Where the voices and
the contending voices

00:09:50.430 --> 00:09:56.550
are so overwhelming that
you'll hear nothing.

00:09:56.550 --> 00:09:59.230
Nobody listens to each other.

00:09:59.230 --> 00:10:02.640
But he does have a
kind of weird sedative

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:06.300
like effect, certainly on me.

00:10:06.300 --> 00:10:09.330
I listen to some of these
channels for a while,

00:10:09.330 --> 00:10:11.940
because you feel that there's
going to be some ferment

00:10:11.940 --> 00:10:15.040
of discussion, which
of course there isn't.

00:10:15.040 --> 00:10:19.110
And then you listen to
Basu and others like him

00:10:19.110 --> 00:10:25.020
who really try and keep
the sanity of conversation.

00:10:25.020 --> 00:10:25.590
The sanity.

00:10:25.590 --> 00:10:27.540
Not just the rationality
of conversation,

00:10:27.540 --> 00:10:30.930
because Basu is as
interested in political

00:10:30.930 --> 00:10:35.230
affect as he is in
political rationality.

00:10:35.230 --> 00:10:38.520
But keeping this going
gives you a sense

00:10:38.520 --> 00:10:44.850
of the politics you are living
in every day in different ways.

00:10:44.850 --> 00:10:49.980
A kind of everyday
encounter with what

00:10:49.980 --> 00:10:54.290
is both constitutional and
what is not constitutional.

00:10:54.290 --> 00:10:56.520
It is in this sense
then that I want

00:10:56.520 --> 00:10:58.110
to welcome you to
what I'm sure will

00:10:58.110 --> 00:11:04.630
be a remarkable set of
speakers and discussions.

00:11:04.630 --> 00:11:09.210
We will try to be energetic
in our engagements

00:11:09.210 --> 00:11:12.010
without erasing each other.

00:11:12.010 --> 00:11:17.450
And I hope at the end of
the speakers' contributions,

00:11:17.450 --> 00:11:21.930
you will enter wholeheartedly
into the discussion.

00:11:21.930 --> 00:11:26.610
Let us mark today
as a day where we

00:11:26.610 --> 00:11:29.730
analyze the distresses
of democracy

00:11:29.730 --> 00:11:32.310
without adding to them.

00:11:32.310 --> 00:11:35.320
Thank you very much
for being with us.

00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:38.340
Basu will now speak
for about 30 minutes.

00:11:38.340 --> 00:11:41.030
We will then bring up our panel.

00:11:41.030 --> 00:11:45.450
And after their contributions
and interventions,

00:11:45.450 --> 00:11:49.360
we will ask you to join us
in a larger conversation.

00:11:49.360 --> 00:11:50.633
Thank you very much.

00:11:50.633 --> 00:11:54.084
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:15.776 --> 00:12:18.170
Can we just close
that for a sec or?

00:12:23.680 --> 00:12:24.180
Thanks.

00:12:27.960 --> 00:12:30.340
Thank you, Homi.

00:12:30.340 --> 00:12:33.550
Thanks to the Mahindra
Humanities Center,

00:12:33.550 --> 00:12:36.200
as well, for inviting me.

00:12:36.200 --> 00:12:39.400
It's the dream of every Indian,
or perhaps every South Asian

00:12:39.400 --> 00:12:42.680
to say, I am Harvard returned.

00:12:42.680 --> 00:12:46.750
So thanks for making
that dream come true.

00:12:46.750 --> 00:12:49.720
I can now go back and say, I've
been to Harvard, with of course

00:12:49.720 --> 00:12:52.450
the tiniest footnote for a week.

00:12:52.450 --> 00:12:55.180
But in case anyone
gets in touch,

00:12:55.180 --> 00:12:57.910
do keep the details fuzzy.

00:12:57.910 --> 00:13:00.520
Because as we know, perception
matters more than reality

00:13:00.520 --> 00:13:02.790
these days.

00:13:02.790 --> 00:13:05.080
Now it's tempting when
you are sharing a platform

00:13:05.080 --> 00:13:08.050
with such renowned
academics to try

00:13:08.050 --> 00:13:10.840
and sound more knowledgeable
than you actually are.

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:13.390
But I'll stick to
what I know best,

00:13:13.390 --> 00:13:15.570
and to which Homi referred.

00:13:15.570 --> 00:13:17.590
Which is to describe
to you how we

00:13:17.590 --> 00:13:20.740
are trying to use the tools
of everyday journalism

00:13:20.740 --> 00:13:24.370
to report on the new
threats to Indian democracy.

00:13:24.370 --> 00:13:29.506
And the consequences of that
reportage to us as a media.

00:13:29.506 --> 00:13:31.510
Now one of the
problems we face when

00:13:31.510 --> 00:13:36.220
we talk about a crisis of
democracy in South Asia

00:13:36.220 --> 00:13:41.300
is that democracy is perpetually
in crisis in South Asia.

00:13:41.300 --> 00:13:45.880
So that makes it hard to
capture the particular nature

00:13:45.880 --> 00:13:49.180
of the present crisis
without running

00:13:49.180 --> 00:13:53.080
into what in social media
is called What Aboutry.

00:13:53.080 --> 00:13:55.990
You criticize the age of
Modi, and you're immediately

00:13:55.990 --> 00:13:58.450
pointed to the excesses
of Indira Gandhi.

00:13:58.450 --> 00:14:01.270
In India we've already gone
back to the era of Nehru.

00:14:01.270 --> 00:14:04.240
Nehru used to stifle dissent.

00:14:04.240 --> 00:14:06.190
This is a global phenomenon.

00:14:06.190 --> 00:14:08.547
I'm sure it's very much
the same case here.

00:14:08.547 --> 00:14:10.630
The moment you talk about
how things have worsened

00:14:10.630 --> 00:14:12.850
under Trump, you're
immediately referred

00:14:12.850 --> 00:14:16.780
to how, well, there was a
huge spike in drone attacks

00:14:16.780 --> 00:14:19.550
under Obama and so on.

00:14:19.550 --> 00:14:22.390
Now this dilemma came
home more sharply in India

00:14:22.390 --> 00:14:26.620
in the fall of 2015 when after
the particularly brutal mob

00:14:26.620 --> 00:14:30.280
killing of a Muslim man in Uttar
Pradesh, a province in North

00:14:30.280 --> 00:14:34.410
India, on allegations that
he was slaughtering a cow.

00:14:34.410 --> 00:14:37.750
And after the shooting to
death of a dissenting scholar,

00:14:37.750 --> 00:14:42.850
M. M. Kalburgi in Karnataka, a
large number of Indian writers,

00:14:42.850 --> 00:14:45.760
academics, scholars,
and playwrights

00:14:45.760 --> 00:14:48.340
returned their
government awards.

00:14:48.340 --> 00:14:51.090
This included the writer,
Nayantara Sahgal, the poet,

00:14:51.090 --> 00:14:53.560
Ashok Vajpeyi, and so on.

00:14:53.560 --> 00:14:55.750
They claim they were
protesting a growing

00:14:55.750 --> 00:14:57.220
climate of intolerance.

00:14:57.220 --> 00:15:00.160
Or as one of them put
it, an assault on freedom

00:15:00.160 --> 00:15:02.470
of life and expression.

00:15:02.470 --> 00:15:04.630
They were immediately
mocked for this

00:15:04.630 --> 00:15:07.300
by the establishment
and its supporters

00:15:07.300 --> 00:15:09.820
for making vague protestations.

00:15:09.820 --> 00:15:12.430
Vigilantism, they
said, is not new.

00:15:12.430 --> 00:15:14.530
And dissent has
had a long history

00:15:14.530 --> 00:15:18.070
of being stifled in
the Indian Republic.

00:15:18.070 --> 00:15:21.310
Which are on the face
of it valid assertions.

00:15:21.310 --> 00:15:25.090
Well, thanks to reporting
by us and others,

00:15:25.090 --> 00:15:29.140
we now have a fairly powerful
evidence, a mix of data

00:15:29.140 --> 00:15:32.050
and anecdotal
reportage, that allows

00:15:32.050 --> 00:15:34.660
us to argue that some
things have demonstrably

00:15:34.660 --> 00:15:37.480
worsened under this government.

00:15:37.480 --> 00:15:39.910
And also why these
new threats are

00:15:39.910 --> 00:15:43.130
harder to characterize
than in the past.

00:15:43.130 --> 00:15:45.020
In my view, one
of the reasons is

00:15:45.020 --> 00:15:48.860
that the reference points
when we speak about democracy

00:15:48.860 --> 00:15:52.600
in distress, about shocks
to Indian democracy,

00:15:52.600 --> 00:15:55.772
tend to be singular
catastrophic events.

00:15:55.772 --> 00:15:57.540
So when we think
about an assault

00:15:57.540 --> 00:16:00.030
against democratic
checks and balances,

00:16:00.030 --> 00:16:03.660
we immediately think of
The Emergency of 1975.

00:16:03.660 --> 00:16:07.830
Right, so I think the
point I was trying to make

00:16:07.830 --> 00:16:13.440
is that the older patterns
of conceiving of shocks

00:16:13.440 --> 00:16:17.850
to Indian democracy in these
singular apocalyptic terms

00:16:17.850 --> 00:16:18.450
has changed.

00:16:18.450 --> 00:16:21.090
As I mentioned when we
talked about threats

00:16:21.090 --> 00:16:23.610
to the institutions
of democracy,

00:16:23.610 --> 00:16:25.410
we think of the emergency.

00:16:25.410 --> 00:16:28.740
When we think about
threats to India's secular

00:16:28.740 --> 00:16:31.680
fabric, the idea of India
as a liberal democracy,

00:16:31.680 --> 00:16:35.400
we think of the Ayodhya
Movement, the Babri Masjid

00:16:35.400 --> 00:16:39.880
Demolition, the Gujarat
Riots of 2002 more recently.

00:16:39.880 --> 00:16:44.160
Today what we have is a
gradual everyday poisoning

00:16:44.160 --> 00:16:48.090
of the collective well
of a million daily regime

00:16:48.090 --> 00:16:51.030
backed mutinies, if you will.

00:16:51.030 --> 00:16:55.170
Those in positions of authority
are enabling the mainstreaming

00:16:55.170 --> 00:16:58.920
at an unprecedented level of
the movements and conspiracy

00:16:58.920 --> 00:17:01.740
theories of the Hindu right.

00:17:01.740 --> 00:17:04.950
So instead of a single dramatic
statement of sectarianism

00:17:04.950 --> 00:17:09.359
by a big leader like L. K.
Advani during the Ram Temple

00:17:09.359 --> 00:17:12.480
Movement, hate speech
has been outsourced

00:17:12.480 --> 00:17:15.150
to countless
subordinates who keep up

00:17:15.150 --> 00:17:18.690
a litany of near
daily provocations.

00:17:18.690 --> 00:17:20.490
What are some of these
fringe obsessions

00:17:20.490 --> 00:17:22.319
that are being amplified?

00:17:22.319 --> 00:17:24.930
As we know, the high pitched
noise around cow protection,

00:17:24.930 --> 00:17:26.400
for instance.

00:17:26.400 --> 00:17:30.540
Possibly as a result of that,
instead of a single epic Hindu

00:17:30.540 --> 00:17:34.650
Muslim riot, like
Gujarat, we have a series

00:17:34.650 --> 00:17:37.620
