00:41:07.310 --> 00:41:09.440
So you can do both things.

00:41:09.440 --> 00:41:12.950
Well, thank you very much,
Homi, for inviting me

00:41:12.950 --> 00:41:16.410
to the Humanities
Center at Harvard.

00:41:16.410 --> 00:41:19.500
I mean, the subject
is obviously has--

00:41:19.500 --> 00:41:21.750
one can approach
it at many levels.

00:41:21.750 --> 00:41:26.400
But I do want to say that
democracy as you pointed out,

00:41:26.400 --> 00:41:28.980
has been in distress
in South Asia.

00:41:28.980 --> 00:41:31.126
Certainly in Pakistan.

00:41:31.126 --> 00:41:33.590
And many years
ago, I wrote a book

00:41:33.590 --> 00:41:37.740
talking about the stresses and
strains of postcolonial nation

00:41:37.740 --> 00:41:40.080
states with particular
reference to South Asia.

00:41:40.080 --> 00:41:42.750
And I made the
point that neither

00:41:42.750 --> 00:41:47.550
was democracy the
antithetical entity,

00:41:47.550 --> 00:41:50.130
opposite to authoritarianism,
but they were implicated.

00:41:50.130 --> 00:41:52.410
And it was about
dominance and resistance

00:41:52.410 --> 00:41:53.740
and it's an ongoing struggle.

00:41:53.740 --> 00:41:57.600
And my only comment
to the presentation

00:41:57.600 --> 00:41:59.760
here is that while--

00:41:59.760 --> 00:42:01.350
none of this surprised me.

00:42:01.350 --> 00:42:05.850
I of course, recognize that
this is happening quite broadly

00:42:05.850 --> 00:42:07.700
in South Asia.

00:42:07.700 --> 00:42:10.500
And I do think that the
media is being targeted.

00:42:10.500 --> 00:42:13.560
But the media is also
part of the problem

00:42:13.560 --> 00:42:16.160
in terms of the way in which
this is being reported.

00:42:16.160 --> 00:42:18.940
I'm not really talking about
your media, your house.

00:42:18.940 --> 00:42:22.830
But certainly I think
that what I'm referring to

00:42:22.830 --> 00:42:25.410
is not simply democracy
in numbers here.

00:42:25.410 --> 00:42:27.120
I'm talking about narratives.

00:42:27.120 --> 00:42:28.920
I'm talking about
national narratives.

00:42:31.530 --> 00:42:35.400
Unquestioned ones, certainly
in India, about the Muslim,

00:42:35.400 --> 00:42:37.260
about partition, about Pakistan.

00:42:37.260 --> 00:42:40.110
All these factors
play a role, which

00:42:40.110 --> 00:42:44.010
give these elements that you
speak about so eloquently,

00:42:44.010 --> 00:42:47.970
the opportunity to carry out
whatever they are carrying out.

00:42:47.970 --> 00:42:49.980
So the complicity
of those who are

00:42:49.980 --> 00:42:53.130
the great upholders of democracy
must be called into question

00:42:53.130 --> 00:42:54.020
here, as well.

00:42:54.020 --> 00:42:57.730
Because without that complicity,
none of this is possible.

00:42:57.730 --> 00:43:00.180
So whilst you talk about
the role of the state

00:43:00.180 --> 00:43:03.250
quite eloquently and clearly,
this is only possible in India,

00:43:03.250 --> 00:43:05.446
because the state tolerates it.

00:43:05.446 --> 00:43:08.250
But I can sort of say a
many things about Pakistan

00:43:08.250 --> 00:43:10.110
from which I think
India could learn.

00:43:10.110 --> 00:43:12.370
Because Pakistan
has a head start

00:43:12.370 --> 00:43:16.640
in how to control our
democracy, muzzle it completely.

00:43:16.640 --> 00:43:19.020
So let me just say a few
things about Pakistan

00:43:19.020 --> 00:43:21.360
so that might sort of
be indicative of where

00:43:21.360 --> 00:43:23.340
you're going.

00:43:23.340 --> 00:43:26.310
We recently had an election,
I happened to be watching it.

00:43:26.310 --> 00:43:29.230
There were many theories
about this election,

00:43:29.230 --> 00:43:30.300
what was going on.

00:43:30.300 --> 00:43:34.940
The most interesting thing was,
of course, the pre-electoral,

00:43:34.940 --> 00:43:37.260
the run up to the election
and the narratives that

00:43:37.260 --> 00:43:40.770
were dominant at that stage,
the unquestioned narratives

00:43:40.770 --> 00:43:44.460
that you were referring to,
as well, in the case of India.

00:43:44.460 --> 00:43:47.750
And it was clear that these
were quite orchestrated.

00:43:47.750 --> 00:43:49.590
These were not just
happening, they

00:43:49.590 --> 00:43:51.590
were orchestrated narratives.

00:43:51.590 --> 00:43:54.090
So there were various theories
about what was going on.

00:43:54.090 --> 00:43:57.300
Everybody was talking about
election being manipulated.

00:43:57.300 --> 00:44:00.120
And I won't bore you with
the details from the census

00:44:00.120 --> 00:44:03.030
to the constituency
delimitation.

00:44:03.030 --> 00:44:05.760
But I will talk
about the narratives

00:44:05.760 --> 00:44:07.080
that preceded the election.

00:44:07.080 --> 00:44:09.810
Of course, there had
been a soft coup the year

00:44:09.810 --> 00:44:13.020
before that some of you
probably never noticed in July.

00:44:13.020 --> 00:44:16.550
When a prime minister was
simply removed by the judiciary.

00:44:16.550 --> 00:44:18.690
But in the case of the
run up to the election,

00:44:18.690 --> 00:44:19.980
it was not just manipulated.

00:44:19.980 --> 00:44:22.770
But there was an extraordinary
buy-in of one channel

00:44:22.770 --> 00:44:24.000
after the other.

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:28.590
Every channel was behind
it barring one or two.

00:44:28.590 --> 00:44:30.620
They fell in line, too,
after the election.

00:44:30.620 --> 00:44:32.370
So what I'm trying
to say is that in

00:44:32.370 --> 00:44:35.010
this great democratic tradition
what you are witnessing

00:44:35.010 --> 00:44:38.970
is a great consensus building by
the media, which then generates

00:44:38.970 --> 00:44:45.800
the kind of atmosphere for these
sorts of outrageous egregious

00:44:45.800 --> 00:44:47.850
behavior.

00:44:47.850 --> 00:44:49.290
I can recount all of that.

00:44:49.290 --> 00:44:53.090
But it also lends legitimacy
to certain actions that are--

00:44:53.090 --> 00:44:56.110
by giving it the
narrative of religiosity.

00:44:56.110 --> 00:44:58.800
Now what you described to
me for the last half hour

00:44:58.800 --> 00:45:01.890
is nothing but politics.

00:45:01.890 --> 00:45:04.380
But what you have thrown
in are Hindus and Muslims

00:45:04.380 --> 00:45:06.630
and it gets some
religiosity involved here.

00:45:06.630 --> 00:45:07.930
But this is politics.

00:45:07.930 --> 00:45:11.760
This is electoral manipulation,
electoral mobilization.

00:45:11.760 --> 00:45:14.480
The same thing
happens in Pakistan.

00:45:14.480 --> 00:45:17.940
But in Pakistan's
case, the theory

00:45:17.940 --> 00:45:19.440
about what happened
in the election

00:45:19.440 --> 00:45:21.589
was what has always
happened, what's new?

00:45:21.589 --> 00:45:22.130
The minister.

00:45:22.130 --> 00:45:22.730
What's new?

00:45:22.730 --> 00:45:25.760
The military has all--
the military establishment

00:45:25.760 --> 00:45:27.300
always intervenes.

00:45:27.300 --> 00:45:28.535
So this is the same.

00:45:28.535 --> 00:45:31.220
The second theory
was that, no, this

00:45:31.220 --> 00:45:34.100
is a time when there is
a push back from society.

00:45:34.100 --> 00:45:36.360
So they're working extra
hard to manipulate.

00:45:36.360 --> 00:45:38.420
This is a sign that
why are they going

00:45:38.420 --> 00:45:40.400
so hard against social media.

00:45:40.400 --> 00:45:42.285
This is because people
are going to be--

00:45:42.285 --> 00:45:43.149
it's effective.

00:45:43.149 --> 00:45:44.690
And people are
beginning to challenge

00:45:44.690 --> 00:45:49.160
the authoritarian strains
of the Pakistani state.

00:45:49.160 --> 00:45:52.700
The third, which I think
actually explains the first two

00:45:52.700 --> 00:45:55.720
and brings them together,
is the role of the media.

00:45:55.720 --> 00:45:59.060
Now the Pakistani
establishment by which

00:45:59.060 --> 00:46:03.470
we refer to the non-elected
institutions, the military,

00:46:03.470 --> 00:46:05.692
the bureaucracy, the judiciary.

00:46:05.692 --> 00:46:10.880
The establishment
has for a long time

00:46:10.880 --> 00:46:13.850
played a role in
elections, of course.

00:46:13.850 --> 00:46:19.100
But this time around, I think
the role was more direct.

00:46:19.100 --> 00:46:22.190
In this instance, it was the
judiciary working hand in glove

00:46:22.190 --> 00:46:26.090
with the military to
get the positive result

00:46:26.090 --> 00:46:28.920
that they wanted with
the media playing a role.

00:46:28.920 --> 00:46:31.970
And so this time what was
surprising for me in Pakistan

00:46:31.970 --> 00:46:34.070
was the attack on the media.

00:46:34.070 --> 00:46:38.360
The main media houses,
GO followed by Dawn,

00:46:38.360 --> 00:46:41.720
clearly the military now wants
to dominate the narrative.

00:46:41.720 --> 00:46:44.510
But as is always the
case with attempts

00:46:44.510 --> 00:46:48.710
at domination and control,
there's always a slippage.

00:46:48.710 --> 00:46:50.960
Historically we have
seen, and I think

00:46:50.960 --> 00:46:54.620
I saw my friend
[INAUDIBLE] sitting here.

00:46:54.620 --> 00:46:59.780
Turkey and [INAUDIBLE] what they
tried to do, I mean, it sort of

00:46:59.780 --> 00:47:01.070
backfired on them.

00:47:01.070 --> 00:47:03.530
You can only do so
much controlling

00:47:03.530 --> 00:47:05.240
to get positive results.

00:47:05.240 --> 00:47:07.840
Because in the case
of the Evren period,

00:47:07.840 --> 00:47:10.190
the youth utilization
of right wing

00:47:10.190 --> 00:47:12.110
against left wing,
which then comes

00:47:12.110 --> 00:47:15.467
to haunt them in the form of the
variety of right wing parties

00:47:15.467 --> 00:47:16.550
that they have to control.

00:47:16.550 --> 00:47:21.260
I think this is where I feel
that the correction sets in

00:47:21.260 --> 00:47:23.750
for such attempts.

00:47:23.750 --> 00:47:28.100
I think that the real joker in
the pack in Pakistan is going

00:47:28.100 --> 00:47:31.730
to prove to be governance, which
I think cannot be controlled.

00:47:31.730 --> 00:47:34.370
You can put anybody in
place, but the real beauty

00:47:34.370 --> 00:47:38.180
of the whole system in
terms of the results

00:47:38.180 --> 00:47:39.912
will lie of who can deliver.

00:47:39.912 --> 00:47:41.870
And there's a big question
mark whether anybody

00:47:41.870 --> 00:47:45.950
can deliver, which I think is
the real issue of distracting

00:47:45.950 --> 00:47:49.170
people with cow slaughter,
with this, that, or the other.

00:47:49.170 --> 00:47:52.070
Which you were also referring
to the distractive politics,

00:47:52.070 --> 00:47:54.320
the disassociating politics.

00:47:54.320 --> 00:47:57.350
I think this is what is
the distress of democracy.

00:47:57.350 --> 00:47:59.270
But my lot-- Am I at 10 minutes?

00:47:59.270 --> 00:48:01.820
My last comment is that
in Pakistan at least

00:48:01.820 --> 00:48:04.190
it's been foisted upon
the people of Pakistan

00:48:04.190 --> 00:48:08.319
by the non-elected institutions,
notably the military.

00:48:08.319 --> 00:48:09.860
There've been military
interventions.

00:48:09.860 --> 00:48:12.890
But I think the worry for India
is that Indians themselves

00:48:12.890 --> 00:48:14.770
are doing this to themselves.

00:48:14.770 --> 00:48:16.670
They are electing
such governments.

00:48:16.670 --> 00:48:19.710
So I think therein lies
the challenge for India.

00:48:19.710 --> 00:48:23.540
Whether you do, in fact, have
people with the right mind

00:48:23.540 --> 00:48:26.030
and boldness to speak
up and fight back.

00:48:26.030 --> 00:48:28.550
In Pakistan, Pakistanis
are fighting military rule

00:48:28.550 --> 00:48:29.970
as best as they can.

00:48:29.970 --> 00:48:33.130
And even governments that
the military puts up.

00:48:33.130 --> 00:48:35.030
But that story is continuing.

00:48:35.030 --> 00:48:37.460
But what is worrying
is the gap that

00:48:37.460 --> 00:48:40.160
seems to be increasing
between how much people

00:48:40.160 --> 00:48:42.810
are becoming complicit
just without realizing.

00:48:42.810 --> 00:48:43.310
Thank you.

00:48:43.310 --> 00:48:44.930
Thank you very much, Ayesha.

00:48:44.930 --> 00:48:47.480
I think this whole
issue of complicity

00:48:47.480 --> 00:48:50.000
creates a kind of fine
echo and resonance

00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:51.460
between the two accounts.

00:48:51.460 --> 00:48:54.950
Ayesha did bring in the
issue of the military.

00:48:54.950 --> 00:48:56.700
Of course, it's a
different kind of state,

00:48:56.700 --> 00:48:59.390
but I think that's a very
important distinction to make.

00:48:59.390 --> 00:49:02.180
But also the relationship
between the media

00:49:02.180 --> 00:49:03.180
and judiciary.

00:49:03.180 --> 00:49:06.770
I just want to mark that, your
idea of judiciary and the media

00:49:06.770 --> 00:49:07.670
was a new issue.

00:49:07.670 --> 00:49:10.790
I talked about distraction
in the earlier--

00:49:10.790 --> 00:49:12.270
in my introductory remarks.

00:49:12.270 --> 00:49:14.870
But I did not talk about
the judiciary nor did you.

00:49:14.870 --> 00:49:17.060
And rather than the
military, we seem

00:49:17.060 --> 00:49:19.690
to see the arm of the
police being used.

00:49:19.690 --> 00:49:21.860
So I think police
versus military,

00:49:21.860 --> 00:49:23.360
question of judiciary.

00:49:23.360 --> 00:49:26.820
These are questions that
Ayesha has put on the table.

00:49:26.820 --> 00:49:27.760
Thank you very much.

00:49:27.760 --> 00:49:28.259
Sugata.

00:49:30.960 --> 00:49:33.490
Thank you very much.

