in a variety of
ways, all of which

01:05:01.930 --> 01:05:03.712
has been unraveled very sharply.

01:05:03.712 --> 01:05:05.920
Not just in India, but in
the neighboring South Asian

01:05:05.920 --> 01:05:08.000
countries over the
last five years.

01:05:08.000 --> 01:05:12.160
So if you think of constitutions
as the text for the governments

01:05:12.160 --> 01:05:14.920
of the one party state
in India and Sri Lanka

01:05:14.920 --> 01:05:17.920
and the military regimes
in Pakistan and Bangladesh.

01:05:17.920 --> 01:05:20.360
The Constitution was just
sort of a road map of power.

01:05:20.360 --> 01:05:21.610
Something that was convenient.

01:05:21.610 --> 01:05:23.040
Something that was malleable.

01:05:23.040 --> 01:05:24.790
So if the Constitution
worked against you,

01:05:24.790 --> 01:05:26.920
you would just change
the Constitution itself

01:05:26.920 --> 01:05:29.540
or amend the particular
provision that is problematic.

01:05:29.540 --> 01:05:32.410
It wasn't conceived of as
a restraint to authority.

01:05:32.410 --> 01:05:33.670
But it became one.

01:05:33.670 --> 01:05:35.950
First to the work of
lawyers and judges,

01:05:35.950 --> 01:05:37.660
who created a series
of conventions

01:05:37.660 --> 01:05:41.290
from the 1950s onwards, which
restrained government power.

01:05:41.290 --> 01:05:43.360
So just to give you
a couple of examples.

01:05:43.360 --> 01:05:46.900
In the Indian case, we see a
broadening of judicial power

01:05:46.900 --> 01:05:48.280
over judicial appointments.

01:05:48.280 --> 01:05:51.730
So we edged out the executive's
role in appointing judges

01:05:51.730 --> 01:05:53.800
and tried to at least
create to some extent

01:05:53.800 --> 01:05:57.550
a non-political party
affiliated judiciary.

01:05:57.550 --> 01:05:59.551
We also saw the rise of
regulatory authorities,

01:05:59.551 --> 01:06:02.050
independent bodies under the
Constitution being the Election

01:06:02.050 --> 01:06:04.580
Commission, or the Office
of the Comptroller Auditor

01:06:04.580 --> 01:06:07.960
General, which exercised powers
in checking the government.

01:06:07.960 --> 01:06:11.890
We saw the emergence
of challenges

01:06:11.890 --> 01:06:13.780
to the powers of
constitutional amendment,

01:06:13.780 --> 01:06:16.840
as well as increasing
challenges to military coups.

01:06:16.840 --> 01:06:19.450
So even when military coups
was eventually justified,

01:06:19.450 --> 01:06:22.096
there were safeguards put in
place and circumscribed powers

01:06:22.096 --> 01:06:23.470
through which they
would operate.

01:06:23.470 --> 01:06:25.870
We saw attempts at crude
force to remove the Chief

01:06:25.870 --> 01:06:30.110
Justice in Sri Lanka, to remove
the Chief Justice in Pakistan

01:06:30.110 --> 01:06:32.830
were met with a popular uprising
of professionals, particularly

01:06:32.830 --> 01:06:35.140
lawyers, who took to
the streets and argued

01:06:35.140 --> 01:06:37.570
the language of the law to
restore judicial authority.

01:06:37.570 --> 01:06:38.600
That has mixed results.

01:06:38.600 --> 01:06:40.670
And we can get to
that in the Q&amp;A.

01:06:40.670 --> 01:06:42.760
The second kind of movement
of constitutionalism

01:06:42.760 --> 01:06:44.800
is constitutionalism as
imagined by the people.

01:06:44.800 --> 01:06:47.635
People who are often excluded by
the Constitution who don't have

01:06:47.635 --> 01:06:49.780
sort of guaranteed
rights in the document,

01:06:49.780 --> 01:06:51.857
but strive to make it so.

01:06:51.857 --> 01:06:53.440
We see this most
dramatically in India

01:06:53.440 --> 01:06:55.810
with the use of-- with the
number of social movements

01:06:55.810 --> 01:06:58.357
in 1990s arguing for
the right to education,

01:06:58.357 --> 01:07:00.190
the right to information,
the right to food.

01:07:00.190 --> 01:07:02.770
Which, through a series of
first judicial activism and then

01:07:02.770 --> 01:07:05.650
legislative interventions
get translated into reality.

01:07:05.650 --> 01:07:08.170
And in some ways, the first
decade of the 21st century

01:07:08.170 --> 01:07:11.350
sees for the first time a
creation of a skeletal welfare

01:07:11.350 --> 01:07:14.050
state in India as a result
of social movement engagement

01:07:14.050 --> 01:07:15.764
with constitutionalism.

01:07:15.764 --> 01:07:17.680
There is an entire
language of anti-corruption

01:07:17.680 --> 01:07:19.554
that leads to a rise of
a new political party

01:07:19.554 --> 01:07:21.460
and the demand for an
independent ombudsman.

01:07:21.460 --> 01:07:24.990
But also a rise for, and this
again has interesting legacies,

01:07:24.990 --> 01:07:28.450
a kind of media allied
rise of popular justice.

01:07:28.450 --> 01:07:29.950
Perhaps the earliest
example of this

01:07:29.950 --> 01:07:32.750
was the Jessica Alal case,
in which [INAUDIBLE] channel

01:07:32.750 --> 01:07:33.940
played an important role.

01:07:33.940 --> 01:07:35.320
Which convinced the
judiciary to sort

01:07:35.320 --> 01:07:37.780
of step in to what was obviously
a corrupt criminal justice

01:07:37.780 --> 01:07:40.390
process and enact a kind
of corrective trial.

01:07:40.390 --> 01:07:42.580
But it required citizens
to turn to the media

01:07:42.580 --> 01:07:45.850
and turn the media into a kind
of a supralegal courtroom that

01:07:45.850 --> 01:07:49.140
would sort of decide
on these questions.

01:07:49.140 --> 01:07:51.220
As I mentioned earlier,
constitutionalism has not

01:07:51.220 --> 01:07:52.900
had an easy run in South Asia.

01:07:52.900 --> 01:07:54.490
And it comes through
most dramatically

01:07:54.490 --> 01:07:56.800
in the emergencies that
are taking place in India

01:07:56.800 --> 01:07:58.347
and in its
neighboring countries.

01:07:58.347 --> 01:08:00.430
However, in the emergency,
there was a requirement

01:08:00.430 --> 01:08:02.410
of the government
to act through law.

01:08:02.410 --> 01:08:04.120
So the Parliament
or the President

01:08:04.120 --> 01:08:06.730
would declare emergency and
the forms of the emergency

01:08:06.730 --> 01:08:07.571
would be observed.

01:08:07.571 --> 01:08:09.070
There would be a
law that would then

01:08:09.070 --> 01:08:10.420
strip people of their rights.

01:08:10.420 --> 01:08:12.628
But it would have to be done
through a legal process.

01:08:12.628 --> 01:08:16.060
And this sounds almost as
if I'm sort of turning what

01:08:16.060 --> 01:08:17.770
is a sham exercise into virtue.

01:08:17.770 --> 01:08:19.501
But when you sort of--

01:08:19.501 --> 01:08:22.000
it's only moments like these
that you realize the importance

01:08:22.000 --> 01:08:23.080
of hypocrisy in some ways.

01:08:23.080 --> 01:08:25.189
Because you need to have
standards to hold people up to.

01:08:25.189 --> 01:08:27.380
If people don't subscribe to
the channels in the first place,

01:08:27.380 --> 01:08:29.546
it becomes very difficult
to sort of make claims.

01:08:29.546 --> 01:08:31.420
What's happening today
in India in particular

01:08:31.420 --> 01:08:36.550
is a kind of, as Sreenivasan
mentioned, death by 1,000 cuts.

01:08:36.550 --> 01:08:39.399
There are no effective attempts
to sort of change legislation.

01:08:39.399 --> 01:08:41.529
But what happens is a
kind of circumvention

01:08:41.529 --> 01:08:43.149
of long established procedures.

01:08:43.149 --> 01:08:45.357
And I'm just going to run
through the rest of my time

01:08:45.357 --> 01:08:48.126
a kind of listing of the
nature of these changes.

01:08:48.126 --> 01:08:49.750
First, if you imagine
constitutionalism

01:08:49.750 --> 01:08:52.390
to be a question of balance,
the Indian Constitution

01:08:52.390 --> 01:08:54.490
struck a balance between
different institutions.

01:08:54.490 --> 01:08:56.080
The Judiciary
Election Commission,

01:08:56.080 --> 01:08:58.450
the Army and Independent
Bureaucracy and media.

01:08:58.450 --> 01:09:00.310
All of which is getting
circumvented today

01:09:00.310 --> 01:09:04.540
either because of
entirely ignoring

01:09:04.540 --> 01:09:05.914
many of the institutions.

01:09:05.914 --> 01:09:08.080
People have not been appointed
to several positions.

01:09:08.080 --> 01:09:10.701
For example, this Parliament
does not have an official

01:09:10.701 --> 01:09:13.200
leader of the opposition, which
means several decisions that

01:09:13.200 --> 01:09:15.796
need to be taken which require
oppositions attendance cannot

01:09:15.796 --> 01:09:17.920
be taken or can be done by
circumventing opposition

01:09:17.920 --> 01:09:18.670
parties.

01:09:18.670 --> 01:09:20.590
They have not
appointed people to be

01:09:20.590 --> 01:09:22.856
in charge, until recently,
to be the information

01:09:22.856 --> 01:09:24.939
commissioner, who would
bring the Prime Minister's

01:09:24.939 --> 01:09:27.010
office under the
Right Information Act.

01:09:27.010 --> 01:09:29.060
Key appointments in
investigative bodies

01:09:29.060 --> 01:09:30.020
have been delayed.

01:09:30.020 --> 01:09:31.644
Positions have just
been left vacant.

01:09:31.644 --> 01:09:34.310
It's almost as if you're letting
institutions die by just decay,

01:09:34.310 --> 01:09:35.939
by not filling them up.

01:09:35.939 --> 01:09:39.402
Secondly and very
troublingly, members

01:09:39.402 --> 01:09:40.860
of these independent
authorities be

01:09:40.860 --> 01:09:43.580
it the bureaucracy, the
army, or the judiciary

01:09:43.580 --> 01:09:46.370
have been given poster time and
positions that are very closely

01:09:46.370 --> 01:09:48.319
allied to the government.

01:09:48.319 --> 01:09:51.620
Be it ministers in the
cabinet or post of governors.

01:09:51.620 --> 01:09:54.080
Secondly, the other big
balancing act in constitution

01:09:54.080 --> 01:09:55.370
does through what's
kind of provision

01:09:55.370 --> 01:09:57.370
of affirmative action,
and the kind of vagaries,

01:09:57.370 --> 01:09:59.780
that go past the
system, is to create

01:09:59.780 --> 01:10:03.950
a representative parliament
that represents a wide diversity

01:10:03.950 --> 01:10:05.540
of constituencies.

01:10:05.540 --> 01:10:07.040
The success of
India's democracy,

01:10:07.040 --> 01:10:08.602
according to
Christopher [INAUDIBLE]

01:10:08.602 --> 01:10:10.310
and other political
scientists has really

01:10:10.310 --> 01:10:12.920
been the empowerment of
groups that were formerly

01:10:12.920 --> 01:10:15.320
seen as backward who achieved
the political dominance

01:10:15.320 --> 01:10:17.190
in legislatures in the 1970s.

01:10:17.190 --> 01:10:19.509
However, this Parliament has
the highest representation

01:10:19.509 --> 01:10:21.800
of upper castes, one of the
highest since independence.

01:10:21.800 --> 01:10:24.350
It has the lowest representation
of Muslims since independence.

01:10:24.350 --> 01:10:26.240
And if you actually take out
the members of Parliament

01:10:26.240 --> 01:10:27.740
of West Bengal,
there would be very

01:10:27.740 --> 01:10:29.840
few Muslim MPs in
Parliament to begin with.

01:10:29.840 --> 01:10:32.180
We have fewer Muslim--

01:10:32.180 --> 01:10:34.580
I suspect we have fewer
Muslim MPs than Britain does,

01:10:34.580 --> 01:10:36.757
despite the differences
in population.

01:10:36.757 --> 01:10:38.840
The third kind of balance
the Constitution strikes

01:10:38.840 --> 01:10:40.845
is between the center
and the regions.

01:10:40.845 --> 01:10:43.430
This was of course
through the early decades

01:10:43.430 --> 01:10:45.140
of independence,
one that was heavily

01:10:45.140 --> 01:10:46.570
skewed towards the center.

01:10:46.570 --> 01:10:48.980
Until the 1980s, we often
saw the central government

01:10:48.980 --> 01:10:52.200
intervening very strongly
in provincial autonomy.

01:10:52.200 --> 01:10:54.020
However, over the
last 20 years, there

01:10:54.020 --> 01:10:57.020
was a sense that especially with
the growth of regional parties,

01:10:57.020 --> 01:10:59.330
states were protected,
states' rights were protected.

01:10:59.330 --> 01:11:01.660
And indeed, the BJP
in the early 2000s

01:11:01.660 --> 01:11:04.220
spoke in the language of
cooperative federalism.

01:11:04.220 --> 01:11:06.740
However, we see a greater
centralization of power.

01:11:06.740 --> 01:11:09.210
And most troublingly,
in sort of territories

01:11:09.210 --> 01:11:11.090
that were ruled by
opposition governments,

01:11:11.090 --> 01:11:12.500
we see interventionist
governors,

01:11:12.500 --> 01:11:14.166
most strikingly in
the union territories

01:11:14.166 --> 01:11:15.650
of Delhi and Pondicherry.

01:11:15.650 --> 01:11:19.460
We see differences in
funding between opposition

01:11:19.460 --> 01:11:20.850
and government ruled states.

01:11:20.850 --> 01:11:23.000
And in some cases,
caste segregation

01:11:23.000 --> 01:11:25.070
of entire populations
of people who have not

01:11:25.070 --> 01:11:26.660
voted for the ruling party.

01:11:26.660 --> 01:11:29.799
Which sort of troubles the
links that tie India together.

01:11:29.799 --> 01:11:31.340
Third is of course
citizenship, which

01:11:31.340 --> 01:11:32.990
is the very basis
of our participation

01:11:32.990 --> 01:11:34.430
in constitutional democracy.

01:11:34.430 --> 01:11:36.200
There are two
developments that are

01:11:36.200 --> 01:11:37.920
urgent and important to note.

01:11:37.920 --> 01:11:39.590
The first is the long
simmering problem

01:11:39.590 --> 01:11:43.020
of the national citizenship
register in Assam.

01:11:43.020 --> 01:11:45.290
Around the 1970s,
there was a compromise

01:11:45.290 --> 01:11:46.970
given the kind of
movement of people

01:11:46.970 --> 01:11:50.210
across the border in South Asia
to have a register of citizens

01:11:50.210 --> 01:11:54.680
which would sort of count
and fix citizenship of people

01:11:54.680 --> 01:11:56.410
who reside in [INAUDIBLE].

01:11:56.410 --> 01:11:58.160
Political compromise
had left this process

01:11:58.160 --> 01:11:59.300
open for many years.

01:11:59.300 --> 01:12:02.690
But recently, it was spurred
on by PIL to be completed.

01:12:02.690 --> 01:12:04.790
And a couple of months
ago, they came out

01:12:04.790 --> 01:12:07.250
with a register, a list of
citizens, which left out

01:12:07.250 --> 01:12:08.950
large chunks of the population.

01:12:08.950 --> 01:12:10.940
While the government
has agreed that there

01:12:10.940 --> 01:12:13.500
will be procedures to
challenge and correct the list,

01:12:13.500 --> 01:12:14.840
the idea is very clear.

01:12:14.840 --> 01:12:17.536
There will now be an official
list that would count citizens.

01:12:17.536 --> 01:12:19.160
And there are demands
to replicate this

01:12:19.160 --> 01:12:20.680
list in other states.

01:12:20.680 --> 01:12:22.950
The people who tend
to get excluded here

01:12:22.950 --> 01:12:24.530
are Bengali speaking
populations who

01:12:24.530 --> 01:12:26.180
live in Northeast
India who are always

01:12:26.180 --> 01:12:28.802
suspected of being Bangladeshi
or being foreigners.

01:12:28.802 --> 01:12:31.010
And it strikes at the very
core of Indian citizenship

01:12:31.010 --> 01:12:32.884
principles, which is
basically not determined

01:12:32.884 --> 01:12:34.550
by blood or by religion.

01:12:34.550 --> 01:12:37.100
But basically
determined by your birth

01:12:37.100 --> 01:12:38.810
in a particular territory.

01:12:38.810 --> 01:12:40.430
The second troubling
situation here

01:12:40.430 --> 01:12:42.715
is the passing of the
Citizenship Amendment Bill.

01:12:42.715 --> 01:12:45.740
Indian citizenship, and this is
greatly debated in the 1940s,

01:12:45.740 --> 01:12:48.950
was fixed to your
parents being born

01:12:48.950 --> 01:12:52.010
in the territory that became
India before a certain date.

01:12:52.010 --> 01:12:54.710
It wasn't tied to your religion
or tied to your ethnicity

01:12:54.710 --> 01:12:55.880
or tied to blood.

01:12:55.880 --> 01:12:58.520
However, this amendment
bill allows for citizenship

01:12:58.520 --> 01:13:01.220
to be granted to Hindus,
Sikhs, and Buddhists

01:13:01.220 --> 01:13:04.790
from Pakistan and Bangladesh who
apply for citizenship to India.

01:13:04.790 --> 01:13:06.380
At one level, this
sounds very benign.

01:13:06.380 --> 01:13:08.060
You're helping
persecuted minorities

01:13:08.060 --> 01:13:09.600
get permanent status.

01:13:09.600 --> 01:13:11.360
However, the persecuted
minority category

01:13:11.360 --> 01:13:15.860
does not extend to other groups
who could face persecution.

01:13:15.860 --> 01:13:20.600
Be it Shias, Ahmadis,
women, LGBT populations.

01:13:20.600 --> 01:13:24.770
But focuses on non-Muslim
groups, non-Abrahamic faith

01:13:24.770 --> 01:13:26.390
groups in South Asia.

01:13:26.390 --> 01:13:28.130
And tries to turn
Indian citizenship

01:13:28.130 --> 01:13:30.930
into a sort of birthright
citizenship of all Hindus,

01:13:30.930 --> 01:13:32.267
Sikhs, and Buddhists.

01:13:32.267 --> 01:13:34.100
And poses a profound
challenge to the nature

01:13:34.100 --> 01:13:36.570
of citizenship in South Asia.

01:13:36.570 --> 01:13:38.780
So just to flag a
couple of other things,

01:13:38.780 --> 01:13:40.490
the most remarkable
thing that happened

01:13:40.490 --> 01:13:41.930
at the beginning
of this year was

01:13:41.930 --> 01:13:45.410
a kind of unprecedented
television conference given

01:13:45.410 --> 01:13:49.280
by four of the five senior most
judges of the Supreme Court

01:13:49.280 --> 01:13:51.770
who came out in the public
and virtually alleged,

01:13:51.770 --> 01:13:53.467
and I have to be
careful of what I say,

01:13:53.467 --> 01:13:55.550
because there are powerful
contempt laws in India,

01:13:55.550 --> 01:13:58.370
suggested that there was
political interference

01:13:58.370 --> 01:14:02.150
in the decision making in
the court about which judges

01:14:02.150 --> 01:14:04.040
would get to hear what cases.

01:14:04.040 --> 01:14:06.380
Assignments of cases were
taken away from certain judges

01:14:06.380 --> 01:14:07.610
and given to other judges.

01:14:07.610 --> 01:14:09.320
The Indian court
does not sit on bank.

01:14:09.320 --> 01:14:10.610
They sit in groups of judges.

01:14:10.610 --> 01:14:12.660
The Chief Justice has
discretionary powers

01:14:12.660 --> 01:14:14.810
to a lot of cases
of different judges.

01:14:14.810 --> 01:14:17.150
There were also a
considerable suspicion

01:14:17.150 --> 01:14:19.970
of accusations of corruption
against certain figures

01:14:19.970 --> 01:14:21.770
in the judiciary
who were believed

01:14:21.770 --> 01:14:23.640
to be complicit in this.

01:14:23.640 --> 01:14:26.240
There was also a
pointing out of the fact

01:14:26.240 --> 01:14:28.760
that despite a long
established precedent

01:14:28.760 --> 01:14:31.967
that the Supreme Court has the
final say in appointing judges.

01:14:31.967 --> 01:14:34.300
The government was slow in
acting on the Supreme Court's

01:14:34.300 --> 01:14:35.890
recommendations.

01:14:35.890 --> 01:14:37.700
And it is perhaps
not a coincidence

01:14:37.700 --> 01:14:41.190
that many of the judges who
were not being appointed

01:14:41.190 --> 01:14:43.190
belong to communities
that were not the majority

01:14:43.190 --> 01:14:44.857
community in South Asia.

01:14:44.857 --> 01:14:46.940
There seems to have been
some backtracking on this

01:14:46.940 --> 01:14:47.780
the last few months.

01:14:47.780 --> 01:14:49.760
And some of these appointments
have been made late.

01:14:49.760 --> 01:14:51.350
But the way in which
the judiciary works,

01:14:51.350 --> 01:14:52.880
it also means that
late appointments

01:14:52.880 --> 01:14:54.588
would mean that they
are unlikely to rise

01:14:54.588 --> 01:14:58.860
to certain decision making
powers within the judiciary.

01:14:58.860 --> 01:15:01.020
I could sort of go
on on this, but I

01:15:01.020 --> 01:15:04.580
do want to just briefly try
to be optimistic and suggest

01:15:04.580 --> 01:15:08.720
what are possibly a few
hopeful areas of opposition.

01:15:08.720 --> 01:15:11.270
The first is that I think
for a lot of people,

01:15:11.270 --> 01:15:14.060
I hope it becomes
clear why forms matter,

01:15:14.060 --> 01:15:15.930
why conventions matter.

01:15:15.930 --> 01:15:19.010
We can always say that these
are authoritarian states working

01:15:19.010 --> 01:15:21.140
through shadowy
forms of legality.

01:15:21.140 --> 01:15:23.210
But these forms matter
in that you can at least

01:15:23.210 --> 01:15:24.810
hold states accountable.

01:15:24.810 --> 01:15:28.130
And I think there is increasing,
at least in statements

01:15:28.130 --> 01:15:30.409
of political parties,
the use of the language

01:15:30.409 --> 01:15:32.450
of the Constitution to
rally around and challenge

01:15:32.450 --> 01:15:33.156
the government.

01:15:33.156 --> 01:15:35.780
Particularly in the absence of
a charismatic sort of opposition

01:15:35.780 --> 01:15:37.400
figure, the
Constitution can emerge

01:15:37.400 --> 01:15:39.984
as a kind of charismatic
set of opposition.

01:15:39.984 --> 01:15:42.150
The second is an interesting
sort of local histories

01:15:42.150 --> 01:15:43.740
the Constitution is taking.

01:15:43.740 --> 01:15:45.890
For example, in the
forested regions of

01:15:45.890 --> 01:15:48.830
[INAUDIBLE] there is a
movement by tribal communities

01:15:48.830 --> 01:15:50.820
which are basically
using the Constitution,

01:15:50.820 --> 01:15:52.520
a physical structure
of the Constitution

01:15:52.520 --> 01:15:54.959
to assert tribal
sovereignty over the areas.

01:15:54.959 --> 01:15:56.750
They reproduce sections
of the Constitution

01:15:56.750 --> 01:16:00.920
that allow for tribal control
of those particular areas.

01:16:00.920 --> 01:16:05.060
Are strikingly breaking with
long history of compliants.

01:16:05.060 --> 01:16:08.330
BJP's Dalit MPs have come
out publicly in opposition

01:16:08.330 --> 01:16:11.360
to perceptions that the
BJP government might dilute

01:16:11.360 --> 01:16:12.920
or do away with reservations.

01:16:12.920 --> 01:16:15.410
The Supreme Court judgment
diluting the prevention

01:16:15.410 --> 01:16:18.170
of atrocities on [INAUDIBLE]
a kind of civil rights

01:16:18.170 --> 01:16:20.600
legislation and the
fact that the government

01:16:20.600 --> 01:16:23.150
didn't do enough to sort of
fall back on it was called out.

01:16:23.150 --> 01:16:26.330
It is clear that affirmative
action provisions and the kind

01:16:26.330 --> 01:16:30.260
of requirements forecast
justice in the Constitution

01:16:30.260 --> 01:16:32.390
are taken seriously by
members of the community who

01:16:32.390 --> 01:16:34.580
will fight to defend it.

01:16:34.580 --> 01:16:36.636
And finally, I think
it's important for us

01:16:36.636 --> 01:16:39.260
to acknowledge that this kind of
breakdown of constitutionalism

01:16:39.260 --> 01:16:42.050
might be new for
most people in India.

01:16:42.050 --> 01:16:45.110
But existent pockets across
the country over all times.

01:16:45.110 --> 01:16:47.750
So if you were growing up in
Kashmir, Northeast or Southern

01:16:47.750 --> 01:16:49.880
districts in
Chhattisgarh, the idea

01:16:49.880 --> 01:16:52.130
that there is that
Constitution acts as a check

01:16:52.130 --> 01:16:53.540
is almost seen as a myth.

01:16:53.540 --> 01:16:55.367
And it almost seems
that our inability

01:16:55.367 --> 01:16:57.200
to respond to what
happened in these regions

01:16:57.200 --> 01:16:58.610
is coming to haunt us today.

01:16:58.610 --> 01:17:00.890
Because we are all
experiencing what

01:17:00.890 --> 01:17:05.120
this spirit of
tolerated emergency is.

01:17:05.120 --> 01:17:05.960
Rohit, I must--

01:17:05.960 --> 01:17:07.070
I will stop at this point.

01:17:07.070 --> 01:17:08.600
Call you to order.

01:17:08.600 --> 01:17:12.350
In the best
parliamentary tradition.

01:17:12.350 --> 01:17:16.230
Very interesting, the notion
of ethno-majoritarian--

01:17:18.734 --> 01:17:20.150
Ethno-majoritarianism
is something

01:17:20.150 --> 01:17:23.870
that you have raised in these
reflections on questions

01:17:23.870 --> 01:17:25.550
of constitution and citizenship.

01:17:25.550 --> 01:17:28.310
And of course one of the
issues that it relates to

01:17:28.310 --> 01:17:31.640
is under the ethnos,
what is the place

01:17:31.640 --> 01:17:34.190
of the language of religion
or the language of faith.

01:17:34.190 --> 01:17:38.320
How is it being manipulated,
but also effectively powerful.

01:17:38.320 --> 01:17:39.680
It's not all manipulation.

01:17:39.680 --> 01:17:41.440
People identify with it.

01:17:41.440 --> 01:17:42.815
Through the ethnos,
they identify

01:17:42.815 --> 01:17:44.690
through religious ideas.

01:17:44.690 --> 01:17:51.220
I think the idea of the
media as a supralegal body,

01:17:51.220 --> 01:17:55.040
as a supralegal agency, is
actually quite interesting.

01:17:55.040 --> 01:17:57.510
Where there is democracy
in distress and breakdown,

01:17:57.510 --> 01:18:00.620
then it is your kind of
investigative reporting

01:18:00.620 --> 01:18:04.010
that plays a role
of governance almost

01:18:04.010 --> 01:18:07.610
or a protogovernance issue.

01:18:07.610 --> 01:18:10.820
I would also think that
the question of education

01:18:10.820 --> 01:18:14.390
that was brought up
raises the issue of how

01:18:14.390 --> 01:18:18.920
the Constitution gets
mediated or translated

01:18:18.920 --> 01:18:22.430
in a more ubiquitous form, given
that you are interested in form

01:18:22.430 --> 01:18:23.900
like I am, too.

01:18:23.900 --> 01:18:27.230
Not simply in the content, but
in the form of these things

01:18:27.230 --> 01:18:28.970
and the institutional form.

01:18:28.970 --> 01:18:33.590
How would these constitutional,
progressive constitutional

01:18:33.590 --> 01:18:37.130
ideas that hold the country
to account, how do they

01:18:37.130 --> 01:18:41.300
get mediated and translated
into, as I said, the ubiquitous

01:18:41.300 --> 01:18:46.040
or the everyday understanding of
one's status or one's position

01:18:46.040 --> 01:18:47.660
or one's mutuality.

01:18:47.660 --> 01:18:49.550
These are important questions.

01:18:49.550 --> 01:18:54.680
I now want to
actually turn to Basu,

01:18:54.680 --> 01:18:58.870
if you'd like to respond
to any of these issues now.

01:18:58.870 --> 01:19:01.850
After which I want
to turn to the panel

01:19:01.850 --> 01:19:06.260
and ask them whether any of
them are to quote you Rohit,

01:19:06.260 --> 01:19:09.000
even briefly optimistic.

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:11.300
I think the brevity of
optimism is obviously

01:19:11.300 --> 01:19:13.370
a very important issue here.

01:19:13.370 --> 01:19:15.980
How long can you hold your
breath and be optimistic?

01:19:15.980 --> 01:19:17.620
Or maybe you take a
deep breath and you

01:19:17.620 --> 01:19:19.006
are optimistic for longer.

01:19:19.006 --> 01:19:20.630
I want to deal with
that after which we

01:19:20.630 --> 01:19:24.280
can open up to the audience.

01:19:24.280 --> 01:19:28.130
I think what I do, Homi,
is with your permission,

01:19:28.130 --> 01:19:32.260
because it's very
sort of broad points

01:19:32.260 --> 01:19:34.784
were made by the panelists.

01:19:34.784 --> 01:19:37.450
Which if I get into each of them
will take a considerable amount

01:19:37.450 --> 01:19:38.500
of time.

01:19:38.500 --> 01:19:41.110
What I did during
my presentation

01:19:41.110 --> 01:19:44.320
was to give you one
arc of the two arcs

01:19:44.320 --> 01:19:46.210
which I described have worsened.

01:19:46.210 --> 01:19:48.580
One is that I said
the idea of India

01:19:48.580 --> 01:19:51.370
as a secular liberal society.

01:19:51.370 --> 01:19:53.590
And the attempt was to
try and characterize

01:19:53.590 --> 01:19:56.080
what exactly is it
that has worsened

01:19:56.080 --> 01:19:57.550
and why it's hard to capture it.

01:19:57.550 --> 01:19:59.980
So now as I tried to point
out in my presentation,

01:19:59.980 --> 01:20:00.820
we have some idea.

01:20:00.820 --> 01:20:02.770
What are the things that
have worsened, right?

01:20:02.770 --> 01:20:09.510
We've seen there's a worsening
of the sort of language,

01:20:09.510 --> 01:20:11.760
the discourse of high
political figures.

01:20:11.760 --> 01:20:14.110
That is distinctly worsened.

01:20:14.110 --> 01:20:17.350
There's a clear
worsening of the attacks

01:20:17.350 --> 01:20:23.440
on minorities using this prism
of cow protection and so on.

01:20:23.440 --> 01:20:28.480
When it comes to the worsening
of democratic institutions,

01:20:28.480 --> 01:20:31.340
some of which
Rohit listed, again

01:20:31.340 --> 01:20:33.970
this business of doing it
through the method of 1,000

01:20:33.970 --> 01:20:37.000
cuts makes it that much
more harder to capture

01:20:37.000 --> 01:20:39.310
and that much harder to resist.

01:20:39.310 --> 01:20:44.470
So I think this whole
business of normalizing

01:20:44.470 --> 01:20:46.810
these sorts of
assaults, and that's

01:20:46.810 --> 01:20:49.400
something I suspect is happening
in other parts of the world

01:20:49.400 --> 01:20:52.192
including here in America, is
something that deeply concerns

01:20:52.192 --> 01:20:53.650
me as a journalist
and is something

01:20:53.650 --> 01:20:56.050
that I've tried to report on.

01:20:56.050 --> 01:20:57.719
I didn't spend too
much time on that

01:20:57.719 --> 01:20:59.260
because there was
a shortage of time.

01:20:59.260 --> 01:21:02.320
And I didn't particularly
talk about the media

01:21:02.320 --> 01:21:04.510
because what has been
happening with the media again

01:21:04.510 --> 01:21:05.590
is very interesting.

01:21:05.590 --> 01:21:07.660
And it's also happening
using the same modus

01:21:07.660 --> 01:21:12.130
operandi of trying to bleed
us through 1,000 cuts.

01:21:12.130 --> 01:21:15.580
So we have a very large
and diverse media.

01:21:15.580 --> 01:21:19.340
We have 400 registered
news channels.

01:21:19.340 --> 01:21:22.210
OK, just digest that
number for a minute.

01:21:22.210 --> 01:21:25.510
And about 100,000
licensed newspapers.

01:21:25.510 --> 01:21:28.200
And I'm not even
counting now digital.

01:21:28.200 --> 01:21:33.190
What has been remarkable is
how this diverse, crappy,

01:21:33.190 --> 01:21:36.340
fragmented,
rambunctious media has

01:21:36.340 --> 01:21:40.930
been brought to heel largely
without firing a single shot.

01:21:40.930 --> 01:21:45.970
It's not as if journalists
are not being killed in India.

01:21:45.970 --> 01:21:47.005
They are.

01:21:47.005 --> 01:21:49.420
It's not as if we don't
have retrograde laws that

01:21:49.420 --> 01:21:50.470
govern the media.

01:21:50.470 --> 01:21:51.800
We do have those laws.

01:21:51.800 --> 01:21:54.310
It's not as if we've not
slipped in the media freedom

01:21:54.310 --> 01:21:57.340
index in the past
year from 136 to 138

01:21:57.340 --> 01:22:00.010
compiled by the Reporters
Without Borders.

01:22:00.010 --> 01:22:02.170
But that's not the real crisis.

01:22:02.170 --> 01:22:06.460
The real crisis is how
newsroom after newsroom

01:22:06.460 --> 01:22:09.790
is witnessing a sort
of internal coup.

01:22:09.790 --> 01:22:11.410
It's the enemy within.

01:22:11.410 --> 01:22:14.560
Proprietors, owners,
publishers, because

01:22:14.560 --> 01:22:18.370
of real or imagined threats
are choking any kind

01:22:18.370 --> 01:22:20.230
of uncomfortable journalism.

01:22:20.230 --> 01:22:22.634
And that actually is
much harder to fight,

01:22:22.634 --> 01:22:24.550
because it's like a tree
falling in the night.

01:22:24.550 --> 01:22:26.740
You've not been
able to understand

01:22:26.740 --> 01:22:28.560
exactly what's happened.

01:22:28.560 --> 01:22:30.550
And I'll give you a
small example, Homi,

01:22:30.550 --> 01:22:33.640
with your permission of
what happened with one

01:22:33.640 --> 01:22:35.260
of India's leading newspapers.

01:22:35.260 --> 01:22:37.340
This is a very
middle of the road,

01:22:37.340 --> 01:22:41.020
you know, playing it safe daily.

01:22:41.020 --> 01:22:43.630
Brings in an editor from
the Wall Street Journal.

01:22:43.630 --> 01:22:45.170
What's the name of the paper?

01:22:45.170 --> 01:22:49.010
Well, Homi, this is all
being telecast live.

01:22:49.010 --> 01:22:50.280
And I'll be indemnified.

01:22:50.280 --> 01:22:52.580
OK, it's not a secret to
at least those in the know.

01:22:52.580 --> 01:22:56.200
So if you insist, it's
the Hindustan Times.

01:22:56.200 --> 01:23:00.086
They bring in an editor.

01:23:00.086 --> 01:23:02.400
Under his watch,
a hate tracker is

01:23:02.400 --> 01:23:04.344
launched, which
counts hate crimes

01:23:04.344 --> 01:23:06.510
and you know, sort of similar
to what we were doing.

01:23:06.510 --> 01:23:10.350
This creates a bit of a stir.

01:23:10.350 --> 01:23:13.560
Within a few months,
the editor is sacked.

01:23:13.560 --> 01:23:16.320
And on the last
day that he comes

01:23:16.320 --> 01:23:18.180
to office or just a
day or two after that,

01:23:18.180 --> 01:23:20.780
the tracker vanishes
from its website.

01:23:20.780 --> 01:23:21.480
OK?

01:23:21.480 --> 01:23:23.670
No explanation is given
either for the sacking

01:23:23.670 --> 01:23:27.110
or the taking down
of the hate tracker.

01:23:27.110 --> 01:23:31.590
It turns out, and this was sort
of widely discussed in Delhi,

01:23:31.590 --> 01:23:35.110
that the newspaper holds
an annual summit where

01:23:35.110 --> 01:23:36.360
they call the high and mighty.

01:23:36.360 --> 01:23:38.651
And that year, they wanted
to invite the Prime Minister

01:23:38.651 --> 01:23:39.540
as the chief guest.

01:23:39.540 --> 01:23:43.800
And the quid pro quo was that
if you want the Prime Minister,

01:23:43.800 --> 01:23:46.580
you have to sack the editor
and take down the hate record.

01:23:46.580 --> 01:23:49.639
So sure enough a few months
later, they hold a summit

01:23:49.639 --> 01:23:51.180
and low and behold
the Prime Minister

01:23:51.180 --> 01:23:53.370
is there as the
chief guest, right?

01:23:53.370 --> 01:23:56.520
But as I said, this is all
a matter of conjecture.

01:23:56.520 --> 01:23:59.890
We don't know for a fact
exactly how it played out.

01:23:59.890 --> 01:24:02.820
But I can list example
after example to you

01:24:02.820 --> 01:24:06.690
as to how journalists
and journalism

01:24:06.690 --> 01:24:09.630
of the provocative kind, of the
kind that speaks truth to power

01:24:09.630 --> 01:24:13.200
is being kneecapped
on a regular basis.

01:24:13.200 --> 01:24:16.620
Editor after editor,
anchor after anchor

01:24:16.620 --> 01:24:20.490
is taken out of circulation and
the organization falls in line.

01:24:20.490 --> 01:24:23.550
That's the whole idea, that
you have to somehow bring

01:24:23.550 --> 01:24:25.050
everybody in line.

01:24:25.050 --> 01:24:29.430
And I think Pakistan, again,
and other parts of South Asia

01:24:29.430 --> 01:24:31.120
are seeing this.

01:24:31.120 --> 01:24:34.410
This has to do with structural
issues of the ownership

01:24:34.410 --> 01:24:36.890
of the media, how
the media is funded,

01:24:36.890 --> 01:24:39.900
of the kind of financial
pressures and constraints

01:24:39.900 --> 01:24:42.100
that legacy media faces
for a number of reasons.

01:24:42.100 --> 01:24:44.080
Again, too many to list here.

01:24:44.080 --> 01:24:46.270
But it's important to
acknowledge this and remember

01:24:46.270 --> 01:24:46.770
this.

01:24:46.770 --> 01:24:48.600
Because all too often
we think of threats

01:24:48.600 --> 01:24:51.240
to the media as external.

01:24:51.240 --> 01:24:54.330
We think of online harassment.

01:24:54.330 --> 01:24:55.944
We think of censorship laws.

01:24:55.944 --> 01:24:57.360
We think of
government crackdowns.

01:24:57.360 --> 01:24:59.140
We think of, say,
for example what

01:24:59.140 --> 01:25:00.390
Erdogan is doing in Turkey.

01:25:00.390 --> 01:25:02.490
Or what's happening to
journalists in Russia.

01:25:02.490 --> 01:25:05.352
But this is also
part of the problem.

01:25:05.352 --> 01:25:07.560
And I think it's time that
we start acknowledging it.

01:25:07.560 --> 01:25:09.930
It's time we start
confronting some

01:25:09.930 --> 01:25:13.500
of these weak kneed proprietors
and publishers and editors.

01:25:13.500 --> 01:25:16.320
And start involving them in
these sorts of discussions

01:25:16.320 --> 01:25:20.040
if we really want to see a
shift in the kind of distortion

01:25:20.040 --> 01:25:22.410
that is happening to the
media narrative in India.

01:25:22.410 --> 01:25:23.550
Thank you so much.

01:25:23.550 --> 01:25:27.000
It's interesting that
unconsciously you

01:25:27.000 --> 01:25:30.980
use the word saying journalism
of a provocative kind.

01:25:30.980 --> 01:25:31.980
You're not provocative.

01:25:31.980 --> 01:25:34.102
It's only that you're
perceived to be provocative.

01:25:34.102 --> 01:25:37.920
You're doing exactly what
you're supposed to do.

01:25:37.920 --> 01:25:38.440
Absolutely.

01:25:38.440 --> 01:25:41.210
Now it seemed to
be a provocation.

01:25:41.210 --> 01:25:41.850
No, absolutely.

01:25:41.850 --> 01:25:44.506
In fact, I said this
quoting somebody.

01:25:44.506 --> 01:25:46.380
I'm not sure who, someone
more famous than I.

01:25:46.380 --> 01:25:50.670
That just speaking the truth in
India has become revolutionary.

01:25:50.670 --> 01:25:51.930
You know?

01:25:51.930 --> 01:25:53.800
So you're absolutely right.

01:25:53.800 --> 01:25:56.870
This is just being targeted
for doing one's job.

01:25:56.870 --> 01:26:00.180
Optimism about the end of
hatred and this sort of tendency

01:26:00.180 --> 01:26:01.620
in India and Pakistan.

01:26:01.620 --> 01:26:05.180
Optimism through this whole
process, what do you see?

01:26:05.180 --> 01:26:06.890
What makes you optimistic?

01:26:06.890 --> 01:26:09.480
I think things in India
will get much worse

01:26:09.480 --> 01:26:10.710
before they get better.

01:26:10.710 --> 01:26:14.036
Well, that is optimism by
another kind of definition.

01:26:14.036 --> 01:26:17.460
As for Pakistan, I'm very--

01:26:17.460 --> 01:26:19.530
I mean, I lack optimism.

01:26:19.530 --> 01:26:24.780
Because I think there we've
just witnessed a regression.

01:26:24.780 --> 01:26:27.600
And I think a consolidation
of authoritarianism

01:26:27.600 --> 01:26:29.250
in a new guise.

01:26:29.250 --> 01:26:32.940
Which we have to wait and
see how it will pan out.

01:26:32.940 --> 01:26:37.320
But as I said, the key issue
here is delivery governance.

01:26:37.320 --> 01:26:38.700
And I have grave doubts.

01:26:38.700 --> 01:26:41.040
But my bigger doubt, and I
think this is something that

01:26:41.040 --> 01:26:43.470
is across the board
in South Asia,

01:26:43.470 --> 01:26:45.810
and why I don't have
optimism, is that I really

01:26:45.810 --> 01:26:50.610
believe that in what I
call the decolonization

01:26:50.610 --> 01:26:52.800
of the mind in 70 years.

01:26:52.800 --> 01:26:58.020
And I think that we are
retrograde rather than

01:26:58.020 --> 01:27:00.930
progressive in the way
that we have utilized

01:27:00.930 --> 01:27:05.370
the need for the decolonization
of many of our value systems.

01:27:05.370 --> 01:27:08.940
The way in which we classify,
the way in which we perceive

01:27:08.940 --> 01:27:13.920
and see all of them are really
from the colonial period.

01:27:13.920 --> 01:27:16.740
When can we sit down
together and discuss

01:27:16.740 --> 01:27:19.310
what is in our best interest?

01:27:19.310 --> 01:27:22.060
But I should-- let
me ask you this.

01:27:22.060 --> 01:27:26.880
How much do you think that these
categories, and I completely

01:27:26.880 --> 01:27:28.830
agree with you, they
inherited categories

01:27:28.830 --> 01:27:32.100
and we want to make them, you
know, in a utilitarian way,

01:27:32.100 --> 01:27:33.140
work better.

01:27:33.140 --> 01:27:36.780
We want them to function
better, but they fail.

01:27:36.780 --> 01:27:41.580
How much of this is also
due to global pressures

01:27:41.580 --> 01:27:46.890
of various kinds in which
nations in South Asia

01:27:46.890 --> 01:27:51.090
have been treated with this
kind of seduce and abandon

01:27:51.090 --> 01:27:53.430
foreign policies of
powerful nations.

01:27:53.430 --> 01:27:54.570
How much is this--

01:27:54.570 --> 01:27:57.390
you think there has been a
freedom to reconceptualize

01:27:57.390 --> 01:27:58.860
these pedigrees.

01:27:58.860 --> 01:28:01.510
There has never been any
justice in the world,

01:28:01.510 --> 01:28:04.110
nor is there going to be.

01:28:04.110 --> 01:28:06.895
We are going to just have
to continue fighting.

01:28:06.895 --> 01:28:10.330
And that's what I mean about
democracy and authoritarianism.

01:28:10.330 --> 01:28:12.540
These are not sort of one
as opposed to the other.

01:28:12.540 --> 01:28:15.430
They are really two ends
of the same spectrum.

01:28:15.430 --> 01:28:19.030
And it depends on the particular
balance between dominance

01:28:19.030 --> 01:28:21.950
and resistance where you are.

01:28:21.950 --> 01:28:23.330
So I think that's important.

01:28:23.330 --> 01:28:25.930
But I suppose what I would
like to say about India

01:28:25.930 --> 01:28:28.930
is that in this
democratic process,

01:28:28.930 --> 01:28:33.690
there's a real danger of
losing the capacity to resist.

01:28:33.690 --> 01:28:36.610
In Pakistan, the problem
is that because of years

01:28:36.610 --> 01:28:40.360
of authoritarianism, nobody
really believes the government.

01:28:40.360 --> 01:28:42.880
In India, I think there's
too much of a buy in that

01:28:42.880 --> 01:28:45.790
needs to be corrected.

01:28:45.790 --> 01:28:48.500
My optimism is very, very
cautious, I'm afraid.

01:28:48.500 --> 01:28:49.000
Quite right.

01:28:49.000 --> 01:28:52.080
And as I said in my
opening comment, what we--

01:28:52.080 --> 01:28:56.710
the real issue was what are the
factors within democracy that

01:28:56.710 --> 01:28:58.540
are justified and
then can make you

01:28:58.540 --> 01:29:00.910
complicit to the growth
of a certain kind

01:29:00.910 --> 01:29:01.870
of authoritarianism.

01:29:01.870 --> 01:29:05.020
Sugata, what makes
you optimistic even

01:29:05.020 --> 01:29:07.390
for a fleeting moment?

01:29:07.390 --> 01:29:12.640
Before I answer your are
you optimistic question,

01:29:12.640 --> 01:29:16.450
may I just raise a question
to bring Basu and Rohit

01:29:16.450 --> 01:29:18.520
into dialogue?

01:29:18.520 --> 01:29:20.770
I think it was very
important that Basu

01:29:20.770 --> 01:29:23.560
did that [INAUDIBLE] operation.

01:29:23.560 --> 01:29:30.160
Because the main perpetrator had
got out of jail, claiming that

01:29:30.160 --> 01:29:31.791
he wasn't there on the scene.

01:29:31.791 --> 01:29:32.290
Yes.

01:29:32.290 --> 01:29:35.230
What's more, that
incident was initially

01:29:35.230 --> 01:29:40.570
being described as a lynching
all right, but an incident

01:29:40.570 --> 01:29:43.900
of road rage rather than
linked to cow vigilantism.

01:29:43.900 --> 01:29:45.100
Yes.

01:29:45.100 --> 01:29:51.010
All that, those lies were
exposed in your sting.

01:29:51.010 --> 01:29:56.530
And then the Supreme
Court recently

01:29:56.530 --> 01:30:01.350
said that there ought to be a
new central law, a federal law,

01:30:01.350 --> 01:30:02.710
on lynching.

01:30:02.710 --> 01:30:05.170
And of course the
government did exactly what

01:30:05.170 --> 01:30:08.275
our colonial masters
had taught us to do.

01:30:08.275 --> 01:30:10.580
They have formed a
committee to look

01:30:10.580 --> 01:30:15.190
into the framing of a new law.

01:30:15.190 --> 01:30:19.000
And I'd like to ask Rohit
whether a law would help.

01:30:19.000 --> 01:30:22.210
If you look at United
States history,

01:30:22.210 --> 01:30:25.990
all the attempts to have an
anti-lynching law since about

01:30:25.990 --> 01:30:32.320
1918 were defeated in
the Senate by a group

01:30:32.320 --> 01:30:35.200
of conservative
southern democrats.

01:30:35.200 --> 01:30:38.020
And only this year
on the 30th of June,

01:30:38.020 --> 01:30:41.530
Kamala Harris and Cory
Booker and one other senator

01:30:41.530 --> 01:30:47.940
introduced a bill, which
will be really symbolic.

01:30:47.940 --> 01:30:50.620
As is evident that
there were lynchings

01:30:50.620 --> 01:30:55.570
of many kinds in America, but
more than 75% of the victims

01:30:55.570 --> 01:30:57.760
were African Americans.

01:30:57.760 --> 01:31:03.830
Just as close to 90% of the
victims in India are Muslims.

01:31:03.830 --> 01:31:06.460
So you know, would
a lynching law

01:31:06.460 --> 01:31:09.280
help or should something
be done urgently?

01:31:09.280 --> 01:31:11.350
Or will we in India
be in a position

01:31:11.350 --> 01:31:14.440
several decades later to
do what the US Senate did

01:31:14.440 --> 01:31:17.890
in 2005, apologize
for lynchings that

01:31:17.890 --> 01:31:19.780
have taken place in the past?

01:31:19.780 --> 01:31:25.620
So what can, you know, the
legal system, the judiciary do.

01:31:25.620 --> 01:31:29.320
Or what can Parliament
do to address what

01:31:29.320 --> 01:31:31.510
is an urgent problem today?

01:31:31.510 --> 01:31:37.180
In terms of optimism,
I can be analytic.

01:31:37.180 --> 01:31:41.680
But I can also
speak as someone who

01:31:41.680 --> 01:31:44.650
tried to provide a principled
voice in opposition

01:31:44.650 --> 01:31:49.450
ever since 2014 and
even before Modi

01:31:49.450 --> 01:31:52.120
got elected as Prime Minister.

01:31:52.120 --> 01:31:58.430
I think optimism is in some ways
a pragmatic necessity for us.

01:31:58.430 --> 01:32:02.800
Pessimism, it will be so
terribly self-defeating.

01:32:02.800 --> 01:32:06.730
And so even on the day that
I first spoke in Parliament,

01:32:06.730 --> 01:32:11.260
I was trying to somehow
lift the pall of gloom that

01:32:11.260 --> 01:32:13.540
had descended on us.

01:32:13.540 --> 01:32:17.500
And saying things like, how
unrepresentative the 16th Lok

01:32:17.500 --> 01:32:18.480
Sabha is.

01:32:18.480 --> 01:32:23.200
If you looked at UP,
there were 80 MPs

01:32:23.200 --> 01:32:26.020
in a state with a 20%
Muslim population.

01:32:26.020 --> 01:32:29.230
And there was not one Muslim
MP elected from that state.

01:32:29.230 --> 01:32:31.060
Only very recently
in a bi-election,

01:32:31.060 --> 01:32:34.820
a Muslim woman has been elected.

01:32:34.820 --> 01:32:37.240
And then also, I think
it's very important

01:32:37.240 --> 01:32:41.416
to take on the votaries of
religious majoritarianism.

01:32:41.416 --> 01:32:45.010
Narendra Modi began to
claim from August 2017

01:32:45.010 --> 01:32:48.760
that the next five
years, 2017 to 2022,

01:32:48.760 --> 01:32:53.600
will be as transformative
as the years 1942 to 1947.

01:32:53.600 --> 01:32:55.870
This is what he
claimed in a speech

01:32:55.870 --> 01:32:58.630
that he made in
Parliament on the occasion

01:32:58.630 --> 01:33:03.500
of the 75th anniversary of
the Quit India movement.

01:33:03.500 --> 01:33:05.540
And he wanted to dominate.

01:33:05.540 --> 01:33:08.570
He wanted to see if there
will be transformation.

01:33:08.570 --> 01:33:11.900
Because the top constitutional
posts, all three of them,

01:33:11.900 --> 01:33:15.470
are now held by those who
subscribe to the same ideology,

01:33:15.470 --> 01:33:17.360
i.e. the ideology of Hindutva.

01:33:17.360 --> 01:33:19.070
So the inference
was clear, we are

01:33:19.070 --> 01:33:22.040
going to see a Hindu Astra
on the 75th anniversary

01:33:22.040 --> 01:33:23.150
of independence.

01:33:23.150 --> 01:33:24.950
And in that kind
of a scenario, it

01:33:24.950 --> 01:33:26.990
was very important
to come to pose

01:33:26.990 --> 01:33:30.740
a different vision of India,
from the vision of a new India

01:33:30.740 --> 01:33:33.140
that was being
projected by Modi.

01:33:33.140 --> 01:33:35.660
That in place of the
untrammeled dominance

01:33:35.660 --> 01:33:38.740
of one religious community
and one language,

01:33:38.740 --> 01:33:44.590
there can in fact be an
alternative vision of an India

01:33:44.590 --> 01:33:49.640
which is based on the cultural
intimacy of India's very

01:33:49.640 --> 01:33:51.600
many diverse communities.

01:33:51.600 --> 01:33:55.340
So in that sense, I think
that if the fight back

01:33:55.340 --> 01:33:59.960
is to take place as Ayesha
wants, then we have no option

01:33:59.960 --> 01:34:05.360
but to be optimistic, even
if we find numerous failings

01:34:05.360 --> 01:34:08.540
among opposition
parties and politicians.

01:34:08.540 --> 01:34:11.780
Who have as yet been
unable to articulate

01:34:11.780 --> 01:34:17.540
a credible national alternative
that people can trust.

01:34:17.540 --> 01:34:18.290
Thank you, Sugata.

01:34:18.290 --> 01:34:20.330
I just want to say something.

01:34:20.330 --> 01:34:28.370
You know, of course the spate of
the killing of young black men

01:34:28.370 --> 01:34:31.470
is not a lynching.

01:34:31.470 --> 01:34:35.260
But it is-- there
is a kind of family

01:34:35.260 --> 01:34:37.960
resemblance between them.

01:34:37.960 --> 01:34:40.450
That the killing
of young black men

01:34:40.450 --> 01:34:44.700
by the police for various
reasons as [INAUDIBLE]

01:34:44.700 --> 01:34:47.290
put it beautifully.

01:34:47.290 --> 01:34:50.080
One person was killed
because he had a hoodie on.

01:34:50.080 --> 01:34:52.300
Another person, another
black person kid

01:34:52.300 --> 01:34:54.880
was killed because he was
listening to the wrong music.

01:34:54.880 --> 01:34:58.850
A third one was scared when
the police car came and he ran.

01:34:58.850 --> 01:35:04.390
You know, these are not
lynchings in the old tradition.

01:35:04.390 --> 01:35:07.540
But they are lynchings
in our tradition.

01:35:07.540 --> 01:35:09.730
There are lynchings
in our lives now.

01:35:09.730 --> 01:35:17.200
And so I think the symbolic
Kamala Harris and Cory Booker

01:35:17.200 --> 01:35:21.010
proposition is indeed speaks
very closely to the world

01:35:21.010 --> 01:35:22.140
we are in.

01:35:22.140 --> 01:35:25.129
Rohit, I want you
to range across.

01:35:25.129 --> 01:35:26.170
And then we will open up.

01:35:26.170 --> 01:35:27.610
But I do want to ask you.

01:35:27.610 --> 01:35:32.770
Whether the progressive nature
of our constitution, people

01:35:32.770 --> 01:35:36.670
describe it because of
[INAUDIBLE] presence

01:35:36.670 --> 01:35:39.370
that it is a minoritarian
constitution,

01:35:39.370 --> 01:35:40.720
it's a progressive.

01:35:40.720 --> 01:35:43.510
Do you think that
there is some optimism

01:35:43.510 --> 01:35:49.600
to be found there by
returning to the Constitution,

01:35:49.600 --> 01:35:52.420
rather like Justice Scalia?

01:35:52.420 --> 01:35:54.260
This is a joke, by the way.

01:35:54.260 --> 01:35:55.810
Anyway.

01:35:55.810 --> 01:35:58.900
So maybe I'll answer your
last question first and then

01:35:58.900 --> 01:36:02.340
get to optimism and the law.

01:36:02.340 --> 01:36:06.010
No, and I would not recommend
originalism for any society.

01:36:06.010 --> 01:36:08.980
Certainly not the United States.

01:36:08.980 --> 01:36:11.380
I mean, the
Constitution is an act

01:36:11.380 --> 01:36:13.120
of political compromise
accommodating

01:36:13.120 --> 01:36:14.560
numerous interests.

01:36:14.560 --> 01:36:16.590
What makes it progressive
is not its authors,

01:36:16.590 --> 01:36:18.730
though they were all
men and women who

01:36:18.730 --> 01:36:21.280
managed to work together
to forge this consensus.

01:36:21.280 --> 01:36:22.870
But really what
makes it progressive

01:36:22.870 --> 01:36:24.640
is the fact that
progressive groups

01:36:24.640 --> 01:36:26.440
and progressive
individuals have been

01:36:26.440 --> 01:36:30.120
able to harness it and push it
towards a certain direction.

01:36:30.120 --> 01:36:33.130
And I would not suggest that
the Constitution be set in stone

01:36:33.130 --> 01:36:35.220
and nothing be ever changed.

01:36:35.220 --> 01:36:36.480
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:36:36.480 --> 01:36:40.360
I know, but I felt like
I needed to clarify it.

01:36:40.360 --> 01:36:42.260
Some jokes fall flat.

01:36:42.260 --> 01:36:43.990
There was a great
deal of inheritance

01:36:43.990 --> 01:36:47.350
in terms of the clauses of
the 1955 Government of India

01:36:47.350 --> 01:36:48.895
Act in the Constitution.

01:36:48.895 --> 01:36:50.960
It's not the document that is--

01:36:50.960 --> 01:36:52.470
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

01:36:52.470 --> 01:36:54.220
But many people,
including several judges,

01:36:54.220 --> 01:36:55.720
are advocating
originalism in India.

01:36:55.720 --> 01:36:57.650
And I thought it's good to
sort of put that on the ground.

01:36:57.650 --> 01:36:58.470
Thank you.

01:36:58.470 --> 01:36:59.700
The second is about optimism.

01:36:59.700 --> 01:37:01.450
And you know, ironically
it's because I've

01:37:01.450 --> 01:37:04.300
read Professor Jalad's work
that I am more optimistic.

01:37:04.300 --> 01:37:07.870
I think what your work shows
is that it's at some level

01:37:07.870 --> 01:37:12.190
structurally not possible to
govern societies in South Asia

01:37:12.190 --> 01:37:14.007
through Maximalist
authoritarian measures.

01:37:14.007 --> 01:37:15.340
At some point, they crack apart.

01:37:15.340 --> 01:37:18.160
And the real question
is who has to suffer

01:37:18.160 --> 01:37:20.960
to wait till that point where
it cracks and it gives up.

01:37:20.960 --> 01:37:23.860
So the second thing
in the Indian context

01:37:23.860 --> 01:37:26.212
that gives me
optimism is the one

01:37:26.212 --> 01:37:27.670
remarkable feature
of any democracy

01:37:27.670 --> 01:37:29.620
has been expansion of franchise.

01:37:29.620 --> 01:37:33.580
Unlike the US, where there
is vast exclusion of people

01:37:33.580 --> 01:37:36.430
from franchise, often from
marginalized and poor sections

01:37:36.430 --> 01:37:37.450
in India.

01:37:37.450 --> 01:37:39.430
At least till now,
these have been

01:37:39.430 --> 01:37:41.260
groups that have got
franchise and have

01:37:41.260 --> 01:37:43.390
participated in it heavily.

01:37:43.390 --> 01:37:47.320
And that has been, at some
level, the kind of thing

01:37:47.320 --> 01:37:49.270
that upsets the apple cart.

01:37:49.270 --> 01:37:52.840
I remember 2004 and the election
results were unexpected.

01:37:52.840 --> 01:37:54.970
And people talk about
the 1977 results.

01:37:54.970 --> 01:37:57.010
And I'm hoping
that to that extent

01:37:57.010 --> 01:37:59.410
those kinds of electoral
connections can happen.

01:37:59.410 --> 01:38:03.220
Lastly, I mean one, I'm very
appreciative of the sting

01:38:03.220 --> 01:38:05.415
operation that [INAUDIBLE]
and I wanted to just--

01:38:05.415 --> 01:38:06.790
when I was referring
to videos, I

01:38:06.790 --> 01:38:08.790
was talking about the
videos of the actual crime

01:38:08.790 --> 01:38:10.810
itself that are circulating.

01:38:10.810 --> 01:38:13.750
I think an anti-lynching law
would have symbolic benefits,

01:38:13.750 --> 01:38:15.830
but it's not going
to stop anything.

01:38:15.830 --> 01:38:19.310
Partly because the regular, old
fashioned colonial [INAUDIBLE]

01:38:19.310 --> 01:38:21.190
record has enough
and more provisions

01:38:21.190 --> 01:38:22.300
to deal with lynching.

01:38:22.300 --> 01:38:23.841
The fact that they
don't deal with it

01:38:23.841 --> 01:38:27.070
is either lack of political
independence and will

01:38:27.070 --> 01:38:30.220
or the fact that we have a
widely unrepresentative police

01:38:30.220 --> 01:38:32.794
force, which does not reflect
the demographics of society

01:38:32.794 --> 01:38:33.460
that it governs.

01:38:33.460 --> 01:38:36.050
So unless those two
things are changed--

01:38:36.050 --> 01:38:38.920
Which is also true of
the colonial army, which

01:38:38.920 --> 01:38:40.630
was also very unrepresentative.

01:38:40.630 --> 01:38:43.660
Which is interesting to see
how these things repeat.

01:38:43.660 --> 01:38:48.370
Well, it's important for
a Humanities Center event

01:38:48.370 --> 01:38:52.090
to show how interpretations
can be creative

01:38:52.090 --> 01:38:56.110
and that my friend
Ayesha Jalal's pessimism,

01:38:56.110 --> 01:38:57.670
with which I have
a great sympathy,

01:38:57.670 --> 01:39:00.360
was now turned into
optimism by you.

01:39:00.360 --> 01:39:02.050
Rohit, I think this is lovely.

01:39:02.050 --> 01:39:04.960
I think this is exactly the way
in which discussions should go

01:39:04.960 --> 01:39:06.940
and negotiations should happen.

01:39:06.940 --> 01:39:08.800
I just want to end
before I open it up

01:39:08.800 --> 01:39:14.080
to the audience
with the idea, and I

01:39:14.080 --> 01:39:16.320
don't know why Adorno keeps
coming to my mind today.

01:39:16.320 --> 01:39:20.920
Adorno said the only way to
live with political situations

01:39:20.920 --> 01:39:26.190
and resistance is to live in
a state of disappointed hope.

01:39:26.190 --> 01:39:28.720
And I think that's
exactly where we are now,

01:39:28.720 --> 01:39:31.440
a state of disappointed,
the best you can get.

01:39:31.440 --> 01:39:33.090
I completely agree.

01:39:33.090 --> 01:39:33.970
Absolutely.

01:39:33.970 --> 01:39:36.150
And I want a hand
of applause for

01:39:36.150 --> 01:39:37.796
these wonderful presentations.

01:39:37.796 --> 01:39:39.245
Thank you.

01:39:39.245 --> 01:39:42.150
[APPLAUSE]

01:39:42.150 --> 01:39:43.300
Right.

01:39:43.300 --> 01:39:48.140
Questions from the audience?

01:39:48.140 --> 01:39:50.350
And please introduce yourselves.

01:39:50.350 --> 01:39:52.390
The man in red.

01:39:52.390 --> 01:39:54.310
Please introduce yourself.

01:39:54.310 --> 01:39:55.270
Hi.

01:39:55.270 --> 01:39:57.910
So I am a recent graduate
from Carnegie Mellon.

01:39:57.910 --> 01:40:00.750
I just came to Boston for work.

01:40:00.750 --> 01:40:05.680
So I might be sort of a
black sheep in the room.

01:40:05.680 --> 01:40:07.300
You are a black
sheep in the room?

01:40:07.300 --> 01:40:10.030
Yes, I think so.

01:40:10.030 --> 01:40:13.180
So this particular
session I think

01:40:13.180 --> 01:40:17.920
is exactly like a manifestation
of a social media ecochamber

01:40:17.920 --> 01:40:22.180
wherein I would
most closely agree

01:40:22.180 --> 01:40:25.060
with Mrs. Ayesha,
wherein she says there's

01:40:25.060 --> 01:40:27.390
a lot of narrative building.

01:40:27.390 --> 01:40:31.750
And although I'm not definitely
the individual instances

01:40:31.750 --> 01:40:34.810
of lynchings and all of that
are definitely real issues.

01:40:34.810 --> 01:40:37.910
I think they can be a counter.

01:40:37.910 --> 01:40:39.910
To a lot of the broader
she was mentioned there,

01:40:39.910 --> 01:40:43.870
and I think it's
important to have people

01:40:43.870 --> 01:40:46.344
from the other side,
too, because there

01:40:46.344 --> 01:40:48.010
are legitimate voices
on the other side.

01:40:48.010 --> 01:40:49.120
And that's why--

01:40:49.120 --> 01:40:54.410
It's not like one side is
the only self-righteous side.

01:40:54.410 --> 01:40:59.110
So I think such discussion
sessions should have or include

01:40:59.110 --> 01:41:01.720
people from the other
side so that we actually

01:41:01.720 --> 01:41:07.300
come to some conclusions
and we proceed

01:41:07.300 --> 01:41:09.470
towards a progressive society.

01:41:09.470 --> 01:41:11.030
So you're from the other side.

01:41:11.030 --> 01:41:12.640
So please give us
some point of view.

01:41:12.640 --> 01:41:13.450
I'm not.

01:41:13.450 --> 01:41:18.210
No, give us some sense of what
a counter narrative would be.

01:41:18.210 --> 01:41:19.530
Well, just on--

01:41:19.530 --> 01:41:21.580
I mean, your criticism is taken.

01:41:21.580 --> 01:41:24.610
I wanted to explore this notion
of democracy in distress.

01:41:24.610 --> 01:41:28.972
But let us hear from you what
the counter narrative would be.

01:41:28.972 --> 01:41:30.430
But also let me respond to this.

01:41:30.430 --> 01:41:32.390
Well, let me first hear
the counter narrative.

01:41:32.390 --> 01:41:34.348
Let's hear the counter
narrative, which I think

01:41:34.348 --> 01:41:35.800
is a legitimate issue.

