And what we need to target
is religious bigotry,

01:53:59.310 --> 01:54:01.830
religious prejudice.

01:54:01.830 --> 01:54:06.930
And you know, most people
in our subcontinent,

01:54:06.930 --> 01:54:09.640
whether it's India,
Pakistan, or Bangladesh,

01:54:09.640 --> 01:54:11.670
have religious faith.

01:54:11.670 --> 01:54:13.920
They are God
fearing in some way.

01:54:13.920 --> 01:54:17.130
But I also think that
an overwhelming majority

01:54:17.130 --> 01:54:23.970
among them are not harboring
prejudice against members

01:54:23.970 --> 01:54:28.060
of another community.

01:54:28.060 --> 01:54:30.460
So that, I think, is
extremely important.

01:54:30.460 --> 01:54:38.370
And that's why I've argued for
a rethinking of secularism.

01:54:38.370 --> 01:54:41.370
That you know, those of us
who were bred in the Nehruvian

01:54:41.370 --> 01:54:49.290
secular tradition had to
reflect a bit, particularly

01:54:49.290 --> 01:54:54.390
after the [INAUDIBLE] movement,
the Babri Masjid demolition,

01:54:54.390 --> 01:54:58.250
and even more so of late.

01:54:58.250 --> 01:55:01.710
So I think if we are
able to desegregate

01:55:01.710 --> 01:55:05.760
this category of religion,
then we would understand

01:55:05.760 --> 01:55:08.160
that a lot of what
is going on is really

01:55:08.160 --> 01:55:17.880
about politics with religious
bigotry thrown into this mix.

01:55:17.880 --> 01:55:22.680
And also, I just wanted to
say that here is a panel where

01:55:22.680 --> 01:55:26.880
we have a journalist who
is trying to report truth

01:55:26.880 --> 01:55:29.620
and is trying to
bring down the hype.

01:55:29.620 --> 01:55:31.810
And there are three
historians who

01:55:31.810 --> 01:55:36.210
were asked to comment on what
he had to say and also provide

01:55:36.210 --> 01:55:39.090
broader context.

01:55:39.090 --> 01:55:41.460
That is what we have been doing.

01:55:41.460 --> 01:55:44.960
But we all have
multiple identities.

01:55:44.960 --> 01:55:49.410
So a few days ago, I spoke in
a faculty seminar organized

01:55:49.410 --> 01:55:52.080
by my colleague Jamal
Kafadar under the rubric

01:55:52.080 --> 01:55:54.700
the historian as
public intellectual.

01:55:54.700 --> 01:55:59.010
And my role in India
since 2014 has really

01:55:59.010 --> 01:56:03.780
been that of a historian, as
a public intellectual, who

01:56:03.780 --> 01:56:11.610
had chosen the Indian Parliament
as a venue to express my views.

01:56:11.610 --> 01:56:14.910
And there, I have
to say, one had

01:56:14.910 --> 01:56:21.480
to face a solid phalanx of 330
members of the ruling party.

01:56:21.480 --> 01:56:25.260
That included Yogi Adityanath
until he became Chief Minister

01:56:25.260 --> 01:56:27.015
of Uttar Pradesh.

01:56:30.500 --> 01:56:33.510
But even under
those circumstances,

01:56:33.510 --> 01:56:40.210
it's important to be able
to articulate one's views.

01:56:40.210 --> 01:56:40.980
So I'm not--

01:56:43.980 --> 01:56:47.190
I don't feel too badly
about the composition

01:56:47.190 --> 01:56:50.340
of this particular panel.

01:56:50.340 --> 01:56:52.800
And what I had to do,
of course, and I've

01:56:52.800 --> 01:56:58.200
got some respect from even
those whom I excoriate day in

01:56:58.200 --> 01:56:59.340
and day out.

01:56:59.340 --> 01:57:02.460
And in a particular
debate that I

01:57:02.460 --> 01:57:05.280
was mentioning on the occasion
of the 75th anniversary

01:57:05.280 --> 01:57:08.200
of the Quit India movement,
I had to call upon them.

01:57:08.200 --> 01:57:10.440
They were all there,
led by Narendra Modi.

01:57:10.440 --> 01:57:14.880
And I basically said that I know
that you have your own gurugies

01:57:14.880 --> 01:57:16.230
whom you revere.

01:57:16.230 --> 01:57:20.520
But since we are commemorating a
movement led by Mahatma Gandhi,

01:57:20.520 --> 01:57:25.200
may I invite you to come over
to our side for the next five

01:57:25.200 --> 01:57:29.340
years and follow the path
lit up by the halo of Mahatma

01:57:29.340 --> 01:57:32.280
Gandhi, who's 150th birth
anniversary has just

01:57:32.280 --> 01:57:34.230
started by the way.

01:57:34.230 --> 01:57:39.180
So I think numbers
don't matter that much.

01:57:39.180 --> 01:57:42.240
And I think you just simply
need a civil atmosphere

01:57:42.240 --> 01:57:46.600
within which you can express
your views and without fear.

01:57:46.600 --> 01:57:49.590
And that's why what Diana,
Professor Diana Eck is saying

01:57:49.590 --> 01:57:53.310
is so important, that there is
an atmosphere of intimidation.

01:57:53.310 --> 01:57:56.390
And that has to change.

01:57:56.390 --> 01:58:01.680
Did you also ask the opposition
to join that very eminent

01:58:01.680 --> 01:58:03.900
prophet in Calcutta, Karl Marx?

01:58:03.900 --> 01:58:05.970
[LAUGHTER]

01:58:05.970 --> 01:58:07.396
Yes.

01:58:07.396 --> 01:58:09.520
I'm sorry, the gentleman,
I didn't catch your name.

01:58:09.520 --> 01:58:11.395
I want to respond to
you and then in relation

01:58:11.395 --> 01:58:13.410
to that, Professor Eck.

01:58:13.410 --> 01:58:16.780
It's really going back to
this question of sides.

01:58:16.780 --> 01:58:19.789
So one is I would partly
blame television channels

01:58:19.789 --> 01:58:20.580
for this narrative.

01:58:20.580 --> 01:58:22.205
Because there is this
argument that you

01:58:22.205 --> 01:58:24.300
have to create a diverse panel.

01:58:24.300 --> 01:58:26.310
So you produce
people who represent

01:58:26.310 --> 01:58:29.250
all possible points of view,
even though in some cases

01:58:29.250 --> 01:58:31.370
the points of view or
even the person's ability

01:58:31.370 --> 01:58:35.370
to represent that point
of view is highly dubious.

01:58:35.370 --> 01:58:37.140
And it is interesting
that this would not

01:58:37.140 --> 01:58:39.015
happen in the case of
discussions in science,

01:58:39.015 --> 01:58:40.120
for example.

01:58:40.120 --> 01:58:43.930
If you had someone discussing
effects of climate change,

01:58:43.930 --> 01:58:46.530
would the television channel
bring in a climate change

01:58:46.530 --> 01:58:47.310
denier?

01:58:47.310 --> 01:58:51.635
Or if you have a conversation
around the kind of Mars

01:58:51.635 --> 01:58:53.760
mission, would you have
someone who says, actually,

01:58:53.760 --> 01:58:57.047
Mars is inhabited by little
green men who might--

01:58:57.047 --> 01:58:59.130
So I think there is something
about social science

01:58:59.130 --> 01:59:01.440
that argues that social
science is not scientific.

01:59:01.440 --> 01:59:03.910
You don't speak from expertise,
you speak from opinion.

01:59:03.910 --> 01:59:06.690
And I would sort of
request and gesture

01:59:06.690 --> 01:59:09.310
that we need to treat some
of this more seriously.

01:59:09.310 --> 01:59:10.750
So for example,
there are two ways

01:59:10.750 --> 01:59:15.237
one can say the government after
2014 is not representative.

01:59:15.237 --> 01:59:17.320
One is that it doesn't
represent my point of view.

01:59:17.320 --> 01:59:19.440
And that's not the
argument I was making.

01:59:19.440 --> 01:59:21.060
The other is that
statistically if you

01:59:21.060 --> 01:59:23.160
look at how the
ethnic composition

01:59:23.160 --> 01:59:24.630
of previous
parliaments have been,

01:59:24.630 --> 01:59:28.020
compared with this parliament,
while it gets 31% of the vote,

01:59:28.020 --> 01:59:31.330
does not represent all those
groups in similar proportions.

01:59:31.330 --> 01:59:33.180
And this goes back
to the comment

01:59:33.180 --> 01:59:35.550
that Professor Eck raised
about the inability of people

01:59:35.550 --> 01:59:36.450
to speak up.

01:59:36.450 --> 01:59:38.220
I'm always surprised
by how much,

01:59:38.220 --> 01:59:42.300
and I think the Pakistan example
is always optimistic to read,

01:59:42.300 --> 01:59:45.720
that even in worse situations
many people are brave.

01:59:45.720 --> 01:59:46.350
They speak up.

01:59:46.350 --> 01:59:48.840
They act in areas without
the glare of the media.

01:59:48.840 --> 01:59:51.190
And they face attacks
in India, for example,

01:59:51.190 --> 01:59:53.400
recently a whole slate of
civil liberties lawyers

01:59:53.400 --> 01:59:54.192
have been arrested.

01:59:54.192 --> 01:59:56.024
And again, it's seen
as a question of sides.

01:59:56.024 --> 01:59:58.330
These are lawyers from the
left and they were arrested.

01:59:58.330 --> 02:00:00.597
But we forget, and I
think it's embarrassing

02:00:00.597 --> 02:00:02.430
that it's changed, that
some of the greatest

02:00:02.430 --> 02:00:04.770
civil liberties lawyers
in their time today

02:00:04.770 --> 02:00:06.120
serve in the government.

02:00:06.120 --> 02:00:09.150
In the 1970s, Arun Jaitley was
involved in the People's Union

02:00:09.150 --> 02:00:10.262
for Civil Liberties.

02:00:10.262 --> 02:00:11.970
Sushma Swaraj represented
people who were

02:00:11.970 --> 02:00:13.521
detained during the emergency.

02:00:13.521 --> 02:00:15.770
Ravi Shankar Prasad was going
on fact finding missions

02:00:15.770 --> 02:00:17.310
with the [INAUDIBLE]
in the '80s.

02:00:17.310 --> 02:00:19.140
And civil liberties
in India was started

02:00:19.140 --> 02:00:23.440
by the president of the
Hindu Mahasabha in the 1950s.

02:00:23.440 --> 02:00:26.310
And one of the first clients
he represented in the Supreme

02:00:26.310 --> 02:00:28.740
Court was someone who
was a communist who

02:00:28.740 --> 02:00:32.010
was accused of spreading
sedition and acting

02:00:32.010 --> 02:00:32.760
against the state.

02:00:32.760 --> 02:00:35.135
So there was a time in India
where the right and the left

02:00:35.135 --> 02:00:36.930
could come together
on civil liberties.

02:00:36.930 --> 02:00:39.180
But the right seems to
abandon the civil liberties

02:00:39.180 --> 02:00:40.920
and the Constitution
as resources

02:00:40.920 --> 02:00:43.060
and left it to the
other side to take over.

02:00:43.060 --> 02:00:46.590
And I think in some way,
the endeavor to move towards

02:00:46.590 --> 02:00:49.470
should be to embrace that
at least common conception

02:00:49.470 --> 02:00:51.060
of civility and legal forms.

02:00:51.060 --> 02:00:53.130
That is an excellent
point to end,

02:00:53.130 --> 02:00:56.340
except that I have
given the nod.

02:00:56.340 --> 02:00:59.480
I want just one,
just a little longer

02:00:59.480 --> 02:01:02.340
and we will be able
to have a drink.

02:01:02.340 --> 02:01:03.550
Let me just--

02:01:03.550 --> 02:01:06.780
Yeah, but I'm only going
to choose one, two,

02:01:06.780 --> 02:01:09.510
and that gentleman
in the white shirt.

02:01:09.510 --> 02:01:10.960
But I want questions.

02:01:10.960 --> 02:01:12.300
I do not want comments.

02:01:12.300 --> 02:01:13.260
Question.

02:01:13.260 --> 02:01:15.840
A little sentence with a
question mark at the end.

02:01:15.840 --> 02:01:17.100
No long comments.

02:01:17.100 --> 02:01:18.210
OK, start.

02:01:18.210 --> 02:01:18.750
Thank you.

02:01:18.750 --> 02:01:21.810
My name is Shamir and I'm doing
a Master's in Global Health

02:01:21.810 --> 02:01:24.210
Delivery Program
at medical school.

02:01:24.210 --> 02:01:25.590
I'm from Kerala.

02:01:25.590 --> 02:01:27.900
And we have issues in India.

02:01:27.900 --> 02:01:31.030
We have issues in subcontinent
and [INAUDIBLE] Bangladesh

02:01:31.030 --> 02:01:33.108
as well.

02:01:33.108 --> 02:01:36.330
Can Kerala be a model
for in there, India,

02:01:36.330 --> 02:01:39.510
in terms of dealing
these issues?

02:01:39.510 --> 02:01:41.610
Yes or no?

02:01:41.610 --> 02:01:42.860
Yes.

02:01:42.860 --> 02:01:44.010
We'll go through that, yes.

02:01:44.010 --> 02:01:45.442
And the second
and then the third

02:01:45.442 --> 02:01:47.400
with the gentleman with
the specs in the white.

02:01:47.400 --> 02:01:49.920
Hi, my name is Asar Pariyo,
and I'm from Pakistan.

02:01:49.920 --> 02:01:52.530
I'm a medical area student
at Harvard Kennedy School.

02:01:52.530 --> 02:01:55.350
I must commend you for
your terrific reporting.

02:01:55.350 --> 02:01:57.750
Because in Pakistan, we
don't find an equivalent

02:01:57.750 --> 02:02:01.006
on the airwaves in any
of the media outlets.

02:02:01.006 --> 02:02:02.640
[INAUDIBLE]

02:02:03.860 --> 02:02:05.340
And everybody
knows who they are.

02:02:05.340 --> 02:02:08.880
But nobody has
the courage to go.

02:02:08.880 --> 02:02:10.890
So my question is about
the human side of it.

02:02:10.890 --> 02:02:13.860
What kind of personal
sacrifices do you

02:02:13.860 --> 02:02:15.660
have to make to
speak truth to power?

02:02:15.660 --> 02:02:16.760
Thank you.

02:02:16.760 --> 02:02:18.440
Thank you.

02:02:18.440 --> 02:02:22.500
And the final question
better be a really good one.

02:02:22.500 --> 02:02:24.440
A lot of pressure on you.

02:02:24.440 --> 02:02:26.160
Professor, my name
is Shah Vassal.

02:02:26.160 --> 02:02:26.910
I'm from Kashmir.

02:02:26.910 --> 02:02:29.670
And I'm a graduate student
at the Kennedy School.

02:02:29.670 --> 02:02:32.850
So my question is in
response to your comment

02:02:32.850 --> 02:02:34.680
on disappointed hope.

02:02:34.680 --> 02:02:37.270
So if you look at India and
you look at the last 50 years,

02:02:37.270 --> 02:02:39.690
we have seen a series
of militant insurgencies

02:02:39.690 --> 02:02:42.270
or resistance
movements which worked

02:02:42.270 --> 02:02:45.180
around the denial of political
or socioeconomic rights.

02:02:45.180 --> 02:02:47.190
So we saw an
insurgency in Kashmir.

02:02:47.190 --> 02:02:48.150
We saw in Punjab.

02:02:48.150 --> 02:02:50.690
We saw something of
that sort in Tamil Nadu.

02:02:50.690 --> 02:02:53.340
We have a very thriving
[INAUDIBLE] insurgency.

02:02:53.340 --> 02:02:55.020
So my specific
question is that what

02:02:55.020 --> 02:02:58.560
does it mean for India to
have around 200 million people

02:02:58.560 --> 02:03:02.490
disenfranchised in
the next 20 years?

02:03:02.490 --> 02:03:05.610
Thank you, thank you,
thank you all very much.

02:03:05.610 --> 02:03:10.160
Let's just have a
quick whip around here.

02:03:10.160 --> 02:03:14.220
The first question is
can Kerala be the model

02:03:14.220 --> 02:03:15.310
for the rest of India.

02:03:15.310 --> 02:03:18.540
This is a sort of a
regional foundation list

02:03:18.540 --> 02:03:21.590
and fundamentalist perspective.

02:03:21.590 --> 02:03:24.990
Which we should all
applaud for its courage.

02:03:24.990 --> 02:03:26.730
But let's get to it.

02:03:26.730 --> 02:03:27.840
Yes or no?

02:03:27.840 --> 02:03:29.740
Yes.

02:03:29.740 --> 02:03:30.470
OK.

02:03:30.470 --> 02:03:31.230
Maybe.

02:03:31.230 --> 02:03:33.140
What price?

02:03:33.140 --> 02:03:36.270
A hefty price in the sense
that I think more than myself,

02:03:36.270 --> 02:03:38.490
because I'm not a
human rights activist.

02:03:38.490 --> 02:03:39.560
I'm an academic.

02:03:39.560 --> 02:03:42.300
And I write mainly in
English, which nobody reads

02:03:42.300 --> 02:03:44.710
in Pakistan or very few do.

02:03:44.710 --> 02:03:47.575
And so the military
establishment,

02:03:47.575 --> 02:03:49.200
with all due respect
to them, I suppose

02:03:49.200 --> 02:03:50.720
don't really care what I say.

02:03:50.720 --> 02:03:52.020
I am nobody.

02:03:52.020 --> 02:03:55.390
But the people who have
sacrificed are amongst,

02:03:55.390 --> 02:03:57.990
one that I would like to
mention is Asma Jahangir,

02:03:57.990 --> 02:03:59.430
whom we lost earlier this year.

02:03:59.430 --> 02:04:03.450
Who has expended together
with a wonderful team

02:04:03.450 --> 02:04:07.080
all their energies in
fighting for the minorities,

02:04:07.080 --> 02:04:08.980
the vulnerable minorities.

02:04:08.980 --> 02:04:11.020
And the price is very high.

02:04:11.020 --> 02:04:14.880
Your life is completely
wrapped up here.

02:04:14.880 --> 02:04:16.950
You can't really
lead a normal life

02:04:16.950 --> 02:04:22.730
once you become an advocate
for suppressed minorities.

02:04:22.730 --> 02:04:26.220
As she puts it, Asma, that
it's not human rights,

02:04:26.220 --> 02:04:28.510
it's not a profession.

02:04:28.510 --> 02:04:29.870
It's a conviction.

02:04:29.870 --> 02:04:31.680
And you pay a
heavy price for it.

02:04:31.680 --> 02:04:34.470
I just want to also respond
to that question, which

02:04:34.470 --> 02:04:36.990
the friend from Pakistan
raised about the price.

02:04:36.990 --> 02:04:40.110
So just to give you an idea
of our own organization.

02:04:40.110 --> 02:04:43.470
So in the past 4 and 1/2 years,
we now have cases against us

02:04:43.470 --> 02:04:46.570
from every investigating
agency in India.

02:04:46.570 --> 02:04:49.650
There's the CBI, which is the
federal investigating agency.

02:04:49.650 --> 02:04:51.170
Income tax cases.

02:04:51.170 --> 02:04:53.850
Cases by the enforcement
directorate, which

02:04:53.850 --> 02:04:56.340
investigates financial fraud.

02:04:56.340 --> 02:04:58.260
These are completely
manufactured cases

02:04:58.260 --> 02:05:00.060
and we're fighting
them in court.

02:05:00.060 --> 02:05:03.940
But what it does is that it
dents your operational ability.

02:05:03.940 --> 02:05:04.440
Right?

02:05:04.440 --> 02:05:06.750
So when investors,
when advertisers

02:05:06.750 --> 02:05:09.234
see that you're facing
corruption cases,

02:05:09.234 --> 02:05:11.400
you're facing this kind of
heat from the government,

02:05:11.400 --> 02:05:13.122
they start to pull back.

02:05:13.122 --> 02:05:14.580
In addition to
that, the government

02:05:14.580 --> 02:05:17.190
has actually taken
to calling up some

02:05:17.190 --> 02:05:20.730
of our sponsors and advertisers
and actually threatening them.

02:05:20.730 --> 02:05:24.000
You know, in not so subtle
ways, that if you go ahead

02:05:24.000 --> 02:05:25.470
and you want to
fund this channel,

02:05:25.470 --> 02:05:27.850
then there will be consequences.

02:05:27.850 --> 02:05:30.930
So this leads you
into a downward spiral

02:05:30.930 --> 02:05:32.730
of operational ability.

02:05:32.730 --> 02:05:34.380
As your funds come
down, you have

02:05:34.380 --> 02:05:35.790
to start laying people off.

02:05:35.790 --> 02:05:37.860
Your news resources are
not able to go and do

02:05:37.860 --> 02:05:40.110
the kind of journalism that
you've seen comes down.

02:05:40.110 --> 02:05:41.280
Your ratings fall.

02:05:41.280 --> 02:05:42.180
Your revenue falls.

02:05:42.180 --> 02:05:43.805
And then you're on
that downward cycle.

02:05:43.805 --> 02:05:48.590
So actually you do pay a price
for this kind of journalism.

02:05:48.590 --> 02:05:50.490
But that's then up
to each organization

02:05:50.490 --> 02:05:52.948
to think whether they want to
continue with it or they want

02:05:52.948 --> 02:05:53.790
to fall in line.

02:05:53.790 --> 02:05:56.400
But this is not just
the case of NDTV alone.

02:05:56.400 --> 02:06:00.330
If you speak to the few islands
of journalism and journalists

02:06:00.330 --> 02:06:02.040
who are doing this
kind of work, they

02:06:02.040 --> 02:06:05.160
will all have similar
stories to tell

02:06:05.160 --> 02:06:07.600
in one degree or the other.

02:06:07.600 --> 02:06:10.170
Let's take up the question of
Kashmir, if you don't mind.

02:06:10.170 --> 02:06:12.790
Because I think that is
an important question.

02:06:12.790 --> 02:06:17.355
We have to call to this
very interesting discussion

02:06:17.355 --> 02:06:18.770
to a close.

02:06:18.770 --> 02:06:20.530
Let's go with you.

02:06:20.530 --> 02:06:22.810
How would you respond to
that Kashmir question?

02:06:22.810 --> 02:06:25.392
So I think Sreenivasan would
actually be a better person

02:06:25.392 --> 02:06:26.850
to give the answer,
given that he's

02:06:26.850 --> 02:06:33.830
been in the unenviable position
of facing voices in Kashmir

02:06:33.830 --> 02:06:36.320
on one side and facing voices
within the rest of the Indian

02:06:36.320 --> 02:06:37.630
Republic on the other side.

02:06:37.630 --> 02:06:39.595
And knows how to
negotiate this better.

02:06:39.595 --> 02:06:42.470
I'd just like to-- there's a
brief moment in [INAUDIBLE]

02:06:42.470 --> 02:06:44.510
book where he says,
the first time

02:06:44.510 --> 02:06:46.150
he realizes there
is a different India

02:06:46.150 --> 02:06:49.640
is when he's on a train going
from Srinagar to Aligarh.

02:06:49.640 --> 02:06:52.430
And a couple of army men
get on and sit on the seat.

02:06:52.430 --> 02:06:55.837
And the other Indians are
like, do you have a ticket.

02:06:55.837 --> 02:06:57.920
And the soldiers were like,
no but we're soldiers.

02:06:57.920 --> 02:06:58.610
We're going home.

02:06:58.610 --> 02:07:00.670
And they're like, if you don't
have a ticket, get out of here.

02:07:00.670 --> 02:07:03.253
And he says, I realize there is
an India outside Kashmir where

02:07:03.253 --> 02:07:04.250
this happens.

02:07:04.250 --> 02:07:08.086
And I think I am increasingly
concerned that I think

02:07:08.086 --> 02:07:09.710
that India outside
Kashmir is beginning

02:07:09.710 --> 02:07:13.552
to look a lot more like
what happens inside Kashmir.

02:07:13.552 --> 02:07:15.860
And I think in some
ways, we are paying

02:07:15.860 --> 02:07:18.680
for not responding to
these territories that

02:07:18.680 --> 02:07:21.550
exist within the Indian Republic
because of exceptions early on.

02:07:21.550 --> 02:07:24.350
And we can't solve what
happens in the rest of India

02:07:24.350 --> 02:07:27.470
without addressing sort
of deep illegalities

02:07:27.470 --> 02:07:29.240
that happen in many
parts of India.

02:07:29.240 --> 02:07:31.400
And this is also an
interesting echo with you.

02:07:31.400 --> 02:07:34.430
Because Kashmir is one part of
the country where the military

02:07:34.430 --> 02:07:36.810
really rule the roost.

02:07:36.810 --> 02:07:38.690
So I think that's
an interesting issue

02:07:38.690 --> 02:07:41.210
of having a bit of
the Pakistan problem

02:07:41.210 --> 02:07:45.560
right in the center,
right at the borders.

02:07:45.560 --> 02:07:47.910
Sugata, the last word for you.

02:07:47.910 --> 02:07:52.115
On the Kerala question,
there is no yes or no answer.

02:07:52.115 --> 02:07:55.770
It's yes when it comes to
access to health and education.

02:07:55.770 --> 02:08:00.350
No when it comes to political
violence of the sort

02:08:00.350 --> 02:08:02.570
that is taking place
in [INAUDIBLE]..

02:08:02.570 --> 02:08:05.420
There is a
journalist, Ule Kempi,

02:08:05.420 --> 02:08:09.500
who has written a very
good book on that topic.

02:08:09.500 --> 02:08:12.270
I would like to address
the question on Kashmir,

02:08:12.270 --> 02:08:17.120
but also the 200 million
sort of disenfranchised.

02:08:17.120 --> 02:08:18.380
And they are of two kinds.

02:08:18.380 --> 02:08:20.550
In the tribal
heartland of course

02:08:20.550 --> 02:08:23.990
you have those who
are mired in poverty.

02:08:23.990 --> 02:08:26.870
They are excluded and
there is a government

02:08:26.870 --> 02:08:31.190
in alliance with
big business who

02:08:31.190 --> 02:08:36.350
want to allow them to take
away the minerals and forest

02:08:36.350 --> 02:08:38.370
resources and so forth.

02:08:38.370 --> 02:08:41.760
So you see one kind
of insurgency there.

02:08:41.760 --> 02:08:45.440
And the hunger index, by
the way, is very high.

02:08:45.440 --> 02:08:47.810
Particularly in
those parts of India.

02:08:47.810 --> 02:08:51.290
And then there are the other
regions, Kashmir of course,

02:08:51.290 --> 02:08:56.330
but also much of the
Northeast where historically

02:08:56.330 --> 02:08:59.630
over the decades
since independence,

02:08:59.630 --> 02:09:01.830
there has been a
denial of democracy

02:09:01.830 --> 02:09:05.890
and a negation of
federal autonomy.

02:09:05.890 --> 02:09:08.690
And I agree with
Rohit that I think

02:09:08.690 --> 02:09:13.090
there are many citizens
of India in other parts

02:09:13.090 --> 02:09:18.290
outside of these regions who are
now paying the price for having

02:09:18.290 --> 02:09:21.510
been silent for so long.

02:09:21.510 --> 02:09:25.490
When these atrocities have
taken place in certain quote

02:09:25.490 --> 02:09:30.240
unquote "peripheral
regions of India."

02:09:30.240 --> 02:09:34.670
So I think that we
really must in the future

02:09:34.670 --> 02:09:37.610
think of one
standard of democracy

02:09:37.610 --> 02:09:41.510
for the whole
country, particularly

02:09:41.510 --> 02:09:45.890
those which are claimed as
integral parts of the Indian

02:09:45.890 --> 02:09:46.610
Union.

02:09:46.610 --> 02:09:50.540
And also, we need to recognize
that Indian unity has only

02:09:50.540 --> 02:09:56.900
worked when it has been
of a genuine federal type.

02:09:56.900 --> 02:10:01.790
We must learn how to give a
sense of belonging to people

02:10:01.790 --> 02:10:06.020
living in regions where
they have been denied rights

02:10:06.020 --> 02:10:08.990
for very long.

02:10:08.990 --> 02:10:17.150
And that will mean rethinking
our concept of sovereignty,

02:10:17.150 --> 02:10:21.340
altering some of the
structures of our state.

02:10:21.340 --> 02:10:25.430
So if we don't
address these issues,

02:10:25.430 --> 02:10:29.660
then I think we face
a very bleak future.

02:10:29.660 --> 02:10:33.080
But if they can be addressed
and if the current phase

02:10:33.080 --> 02:10:35.120
of religious
majoritarianism results

02:10:35.120 --> 02:10:40.340
in a new kind of politics, a
new kind of democratic politics,

02:10:40.340 --> 02:10:42.740
and a new federalism in India.

02:10:42.740 --> 02:10:45.760
Then perhaps we
can be optimistic,

02:10:45.760 --> 02:10:49.400
as I think our
chairman would like.

02:10:49.400 --> 02:10:51.900
With a touch of disappointment.

02:10:51.900 --> 02:10:53.150
To keep us sharp.

02:10:53.150 --> 02:10:57.200
Perhaps the disappointments
will recede and hope will rise.

02:10:57.200 --> 02:10:58.710
Well, thank you so much.

02:10:58.710 --> 02:11:00.125
I want to thank Basu.

02:11:00.125 --> 02:11:03.740
Basu for being here and
giving us this occasion

02:11:03.740 --> 02:11:05.730
for having this discussion.

02:11:05.730 --> 02:11:06.810
Thank you.

02:11:06.810 --> 02:11:11.460
And all my panelists for
a wonderful participation.

02:11:11.460 --> 02:11:14.310
I think we were not of one mind.

02:11:14.310 --> 02:11:17.030
But I think we did what
universities could best do,

02:11:17.030 --> 02:11:19.730
which is have moments
of convergence.

02:11:19.730 --> 02:11:21.230
We come from
different places, we

02:11:21.230 --> 02:11:23.570
may go to other
places or other ideas.

02:11:23.570 --> 02:11:26.570
But these convergent moments,
these consulations are I

02:11:26.570 --> 02:11:28.460
think extremely important.

02:11:28.460 --> 02:11:33.110
And we will try as best we can
to keep this discussion going.

02:11:33.110 --> 02:11:36.040
Because the country,
our countries here,

02:11:36.040 --> 02:11:38.870
are precious to us.

02:11:38.870 --> 02:11:40.970
They're inspirational to us.

02:11:40.970 --> 02:11:44.320
And yet, they are in extremis.

02:11:44.320 --> 02:11:47.570
And I think we need to speak
from wherever we happen to be.

02:11:47.570 --> 02:11:48.380
Thank you.

02:11:48.380 --> 02:11:50.190
Thank you very much
for being here.

02:11:50.190 --> 02:11:53.540
[APPLAUSE]

